<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's non-oil exports reached 930 million U.S.
dollars in the first four months of the current Iranian calendar
year starting March 21, 11.8 percent lower than the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the customs department, carpets are the largest
non-oil export item in the four-month period, reaching 155 million
dollars. The figure, however, was a 4.2 percent decrease compared
to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Chemicals came second at 99 million dollars, showing a sharp
fall of a 47.7 percent from the same period of last year. Pistachio
ranked third at 77 million dollars, which was 45 percent lower than
the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The department also said that imports of the country over the
four-month period was as high as 4.53 million dollars, a 4 percent
higher than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Main imported goods are machinery, metals, electrical
appliances, wheat and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Governor of the Central Bank of Egypt, Ismail Hassan,
said the country's foreign exchange reserves were stabilized and
the foreign debts went down.
</P>
<P>
The bank's new board of directors reviewed in its meeting on
Thursday the financial positions of Egyptian banks and the ratios
of bank reserves and fluidity and their applicability to legal
ratios, he added.
</P>
<P>
The share quotas of some state-owned banks in joint banks have
been raised, Hassan pointed out, adding that the bank's board
followed the implementation of bank budgets of fiscal year 1999-
2000.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel'S economic growth rate will hover between 5.
5 and 6 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
While Israeli economists predicted a 3-percent growth rate, the
Israeli Ministry of Finance and the Central Bank of Israel (CBI)
said in July the percentage hiked to 4.5 since the beginning of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Israel will maintain the growth rate of 5.5-6 percent over the
coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The rate of unemployment went down from 8.9 percent at the end
of 1999 to 8.6 percent in the first six months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An economic delegation from the Chinese province of
Jiangsu wound up a six-day visit Friday to Egypt during which they
discussed with Egyptian officials the investment potentials in
Egypt in the light of friendly ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Raga'ie, first undersecretary of the Egyptian Ministry of
International Cooperation and chief of Section of Cooperation with
Asia, Australia, Canada and Latin America, said he reviewed with
the Chinese delegation the investment areas and promising
investment environment in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
