<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian-Iraqi Joint Committee Resumes Work After 20-Year Halt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammed
Mahdi Saleh and his party arrived here Friday afternoon to attend
the meeting of the Syrian-Iraqi Joint Ministerial Committee, the
first over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Saleh told reporters that he would discuss
with Syrian leaders ways of enhancing economic, trade and
scientific cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also discuss the resumption of technical and
cultural ties and cooperation in the field of land and marine
transport, including exploitation of the Syrian Latakia seaport as
a transit point for Iraqi imports.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Syria have recently signed an agreement on Iraq's
importation of 1 million tons of commodities through the Syrian
Tartous port this year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the preparations for the meeting, Saleh visited
Damascus in July and a Syrian economic delegation has visited the
Iraqi capital of Baghdad recently.
</P>
<P>
During the preparatory meetings, an agreement was reached on
convening the meetings of the joint committee, from August, in
Damascus and Baghdad alternately.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Iraqi ties, severed since 1980 due to Syria's support
to Iran in the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war, have been improving since
1997. Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Said Al-Sahaf visited Syria
in June to attend the funeral of late Syrian President Hafez Al-
Assad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
