<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Oil Officials Say Baku-Ceyhan Project "Unfeasible" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Baku-Ceyhan pipeline, aimed at
transferring Caspian oil to western markets via Turkey, is "
unfeasible" and unlikely to be realized in the near future, Iranian
Deputy Oil Minister Muhammad Nejad has said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Turkish Daily News on Wednesday, Nejad said
that Tehran considered the Baku-Ceyhan project to be "uneconomical"
and difficult to be constructed due to its route.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-backed project, signed by Turkey, Azerbaijan and
Georgia on the sidelines of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) summit in Istanbul last November, will
run from the Azerbaijani capital of Baku via Georgia to a Turkish
terminal at Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the 2,000-kilometre pipeline is estimated at between
2.7 and 3.3 billion U.S. dollars and should become operational in
2004.
</P>
<P>
The paper published on Friday quoted the Iranian minister as
saying that even though Turkey and the United States had worked
intensively on the project, "it was clear that the route was not
practical."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has promoted the Baku-Ceyhan project and rejected
alternative routes, including one going through Russian and another
one through Iran, in a bid to curb its strategic rivals Moscow and
Tehran's influence over Central Asia and the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Nejad said that even if the Baku-Ceyhan project should succeed
eventually, "it will without doubt take a long time."
</P>
<P>
Nejad, who concluded his two-day visit to Ankara on Wednesday,
signed a protocol with Turkey regarding Iran's supplying natural
gas to the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, Turkey promises to buy 3 billion cubic
metres of gas annually from Iran as of July 30, 2001 by a pipeline
linking Tabriz in northwestern Iran to Ankara, which is still under
construction.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1996 agreement, Turkey pledged to buy natural gas from
Iran for 23 years, supplied by the pipeline, and complete its
section of the conduit by January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
But it has failed to meet the deadline and said in February that
it will not be able to complete the pipeline until the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
With full U.S. backing, Turkey is pursuing a multi-million
dollar pipeline project -- which excludes routes through both
Russia and Iran -- to carry natural gas from Turkmenistan through
the Caspian Sea to western markets via Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has voiced opposition to the Turkish-Iranian deal on
the grounds that it was a rival to the trans-Caspian gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
To appease Washington, Ankara has repeatedly said the trans-
Caspian pipeline is a priority and ever postponed the construction
of the Tabriz-Ankara pipeline.
</P>
<P>
But the completion of the trans-Caspian gas pipeline, as well as
the Baku-Ceyhan oil project, seems nowhere in sight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Unveils Monetary Policy Measures to Stabilize Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
Friday announced a number of monetary policy measures as part of
the already endorsed package of short-term measures meant to
stabilize the economy.
</P>
<P>
The measures focus on the review of the bank rate, concessional
export finance facility, corporate foreign currency accounts for
gold producers and lending rates, all in the aim of limiting the
adverse effects of the budget deficit on money supply and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The measures, long awaited by the business community, came in
the wake of Tuesday's 25 percent devaluation of the Zimbabwean
dollar and Thursday's short-term government expenditure control
instruments announced in the parliament by Finance and Economic
Development Minister Simba Makoni.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in a statement that it would effectively
lower the bank rate by 12 percent to 61.7 percent and maintain it
within a range of 2 to 2.5 percentage points above the rate of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
"This rate will be reviewed from time to time and such review
will take cognizance of actual inflation as well as trends in
aggregate demand," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction of inflation remains critical for economic
growth to occur," it noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the bank would simultaneously
release 50 percent of the pool of commercial and merchant bank
statutory reserves for onlending to exporters at an all inclusive
concessional final interest rate of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would make available about 100 million U.S. dollars for
onlending to export sectors through 180-day pre- and post-shipment
export bills drawn on and accepted by banks, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
This arrangement, the statement said, should provide a quick
supply response to enhance foreign currency availability, thereby
stimulating the productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the reduction in the bank rate and the
release of statutory reserves for use by banks would significantly
lower the cost of funds by as much as 15 to 20 percent for
commercial and merchant banks.
</P>
<P>
The first half of the year has shown that the Zimbabwean
economy was in a deep inflation mode, with the year-on-year rate
of inflation rising to 59.3 percent by June from 48.9 percent in
February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
