<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 500 Foreigners Detained in Western Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 500 foreigners,
mostly refugees from neighboring Burundi and Rwanda, are being
detained or serving their sentences in prisons in Tanzania's
western Kagera region for various crimes ranging from armed
robbery to rape.
</P>
<P>
Such a big number of offenders contribute a lot to the
congestion of inmates in local prisons, said Kagera regional
prison officer Luxas Mwitwa while briefing Minister for Home
Affairs Mohamed Seif Khatib on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khatib is on a four-day inspection tour of refugee camps in the
western regions.
</P>
<P>
According to Mwitwa, of the 477 foreigners in Kagera prisons,
267 are Burundians, 187 Rwandans, 22 Ugandans and one Kenyan.
</P>
<P>
Citing the Ngara district prison as an example, Mwitwa said
almost half of the inmates there are refugees from Burundi and
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
He said the prison, which was expanded recently under the
facilitation of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees,
has the capacity of accommodating 186 inmates, but presently it is
congested with 457 inmates.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the wave of crime involving refugees in the
region is on the decrease, despite enhanced security by the police
and the army forces in refugee camps and along the border.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is home to over 800,000 refugees from Burundi, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Somalia, Sudan,
Rwanda and Uganda. However, more than 450,000 refugees nation-wide
are not residing in camps or settlements.
</P>
<P>
The influx of refugees has resulted in the increase of
illegally owned firearms, most of which are used in armed
robberies involving murders, according to Tanzanian authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
