<HEADLINE> Former Botswana President to Push Congolese Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The facilitator in the
political dialogue of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
and former Botswana president Ketumile Masire is to brief the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit on the inter-
Congolese peace talks, South African Press Association reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state from 14 SADC member countries including the
DRC will meet in the Namibian capital of Windhoek on Sunday and
Monday to assess their role in bringing peace to the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
"It will be up to the heads of states as to whether they will
help him (Masire) to persuade DRC President Laurent Kabila to
cooperate," Masire's spokesman Archibold Mogwe said.
</P>
<P>
"Whether that will lead to a breakthrough leading to peace
talks is everybody's guess," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, backed by forces from Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola, has
been fighting rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda since August 1998
and a peace deal signed in Lusaka last year has failed to halt the
conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
