<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile to Seek Free Trade Agreement with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chile would surmount with this free trade agreement the
competitive disadvantage that affects its most important exports
that compete in the United States with Canada and Mexico, said
Rosales.
</P>
<P>
According to Rosales, Chile needs a platform that will permit
negotiate a free trade agreement with the United States when the
new U.S. administration arrives.
</P>
<P>
The next U.S. administration, whether Republican or Democrat,
will request the U.S. Congress to discuss the Free Trade Area of
the Americas (FTAA), and when this occurs, it will benefit Chile,
said Rosales.
</P>
<P>
Rosales met Alicia Frohmann, head of the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA) Department.
</P>
<P>
Frohmann said that her department wants to determine the date
for the completion of this negotiation, "so we have set the year
2003 as the deadline and 2004 for the ratification, for the
agreement to be in force in 2005."
</P>
<P>
The United States is Chile's first trade partner, so the
Chilean authorities see necessary to negotiate a free trade
agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of Chilean exports go to the United States,
and last year they amounted to the unprecedented figure of 3.088
billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
