<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Regrets at Cancellation of Visits Between Cyprus Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Friday
expressed regret at the cancellation of exchange of visits between
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. heard late Thursday afternoon from the Turkish
Cypriots that they will not agree to the Greek Cypriot request to
have the check point at Strovilia removed and the measures against
UNFICYP (U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus) lifted," spokeswoman
for the U.N. Sarah Russell said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriots had planned to visit the monastery of
Apostolos Andreas in Turkish Cypriot area and Turkish Cypriots to
the village of Kokkina in Greek Cypriot area.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government had told the U.N. that it would not allow
safe passage for some 800 Turkish Cypriots to go to Kokkina, on the
northwestern part of the island, unless the Turkish Cypriot regime
lifted the restrictive measures it is implementing against the U.
N..
</P>
<P>
It has also said a recently-set-up Turkish army checkpoint at
Strovilia village on the eastern part of the island violates the
status quo in the area and should be removed.
</P>
<P>
Russell said that following the reply from the Turkish Cypriots
neither visit will take place.
</P>
<P>
"Such visits are an important element in our work to retain
normal conditions and bring the two communities closer together,"
she said, expressing "regret" at their cancellation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the Mediterranean island after a failed pro-
Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, nearly 1,200 Greek Cypriots had
planned to visit the monastery of Apostolos Andreas on August 15,
an important date in the Greek Orthodox religion.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 Turkish Cypriots had been scheduled to visit the
memorial of those killed at Kokkina in the 1964 conflict on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Just before the third round of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks in
early July the Turkish army advanced in Strovilia, in southeast
Cyprus, and set up a military outpost enclaving a small number of
Greek Cypriot families.
</P>
<P>
The move was part of retaliation measures of the Turkish Cypriot
side after the U.N. Security Council refused to give it a say in
the deployment of the United Nations Peacekeeping Force (UNFICYP).
</P>
</TEXT>
