<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Occupiers to Stay on Designated Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe insisted on Friday
that black war veterans and peasants will not be removed from the
occupied white-owned farms earmarked for acquisition under the
resettlement program, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
However, occupiers will be removed from non-designated farms,
Zimbabwean Information Minister Jonathan Moyo told a press
conference during the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
council of ministers meeting in the Namibian capital of Windhoek
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has identified a total of 3,041 farms
or some five million hectares of farmland for acquisition.
</P>
<P>
When he addressed members of the Commercial Farmers' Union in
Bindura, Zimbabwe, on Thursday, President Robert Mugabe
backtracked on an apparent undertaking to remove self-styled
veterans from the more than a thousand white-owned farms they have
occupied since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Zimbabwe wishes to make it quite clear that
there has been no change whatsoever in the land reform policy,"
Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government stands firm in its intention to
complete the removal of 500,000 landless families to the
designated land before the start of this year's rainy season in
October.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Lands and Resettlement Minister Joseph Made,
speaking at the same briefing, said that to date about 211 land
acquisition orders have been served for farms on an original list
of 804 properties. 
</P>
