<HEADLINE> French Investigators Find Metal Strip on Runway of Crashed Concorde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- French investigators have found a
thin metal strip of 40 centimeters on the runway of the Air France
Concorde supersonic aircraft which crashed Tuesday last week, said
the Bureau of Accident Investigation (BEA) on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The metal strip was found among the debris on the runway and it
did not belong to any part of the plane, said BEA.
</P>
<P>
But the investigators still cannot draw any conclusion from the
new finding.
</P>
<P>
The BEA said that one of the wheels on the left-wing of
Concorde was replaced before the take-off, but the wheel was found
among the wreckage and its tire had not burst.
</P>
<P>
Among the debris found by BEA on the runway was the piece of a
machine which served to avoid the injection of water into the
engine when the runway was wet, and a piece of a valve which
served to protect the undercarriage.
</P>
<P>
The investigators also found that the plane leant toward the
left when it was taking off.
</P>
<P>
They said that the debris of tire found on the runway more
probably belongs to one tire instead of two.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and fourteen people were killed in the Concorde
crash, 96 of them German tourists. 
</P>
