<HEADLINE> Cyprus Solution Not Expected in 2000: U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Alvaro de Soto, United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan's special adviser for Cyprus, said
Friday that he doubted whether a Cyprus solution could be found by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closure of the third round of U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks on Cyprus in Geneva, which started on July 5, de
Soto said the two sides of the island will meet again on September
12 in New York.
</P>
<P>
De Soto said the whole process is about building bridges and it
is ongoing and that one must see the talks in the long term.
</P>
<P>
The only satisfying result, he said, would be one which
satisfies all Cypriots and in which no one is a loser or a winner.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the eastern Mediterranean island after a failed
coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks had been held
between the two communities since December 1999, aimed at preparing
the ground for substantive negotiations leading to a comprehensive
settlement.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, de Soto had separate meetings
with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash on Friday, the last day of the third round.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with de Soto, Clerides said the Greek
Cypriot side will discuss and analyze its positions. He did not
reply to other press questions because of a news blackout imposed
by the U.N. on the talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash, on his side, said he is satisfied that he has put
forward his positions during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side wants a bizonal, bicommunal federal
republic in Cyprus, while the Turkish Cypriot side is now demanding
a loose confederation of two separate states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Unchanged in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in the
United States remained at 4 percent in July despite the loss of
108,000 jobs during the month, the Labor Department reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
All of the jobs lost came from 290,000 temporary government
workers laid off in July because their work on the census was
finished.
</P>
<P>
The private sector actually added 138,000 jobs in the month, a
sign that the nation's labor market remained extremely tight. The
strength was spread across a number of sectors with manufacturing,
financial services and retail trade all posting strong gains.
</P>
<P>
The nation's jobless rate dipped to a 30-year low of 3.9
percent in April, rose to 4.1 percent in May and then edged down
to hold at 4 percent in June and July.
</P>
<P>
The tight labor markets and the difficulty employers are having
in filling jobs was seen in a further rise in average hourly
earnings, which climbed by 0.4 percent in July to 13.76 U.S.
dollars an hour, an acceleration from gains of 0.3 percent in June
and 0.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
For July, the drop in payroll jobs of 108,000 was the first
decline since a fall of 69,000 in January 1996, a decline blamed
on severe winter weather. And it was the biggest drop since a fall
of 185,000 in April 1991, a period when the country was struggling
to pull out of the 1990-91 recession.
</P>
<P>
The rise in private sector jobs of 138,000 indicated that the
economy has continued to power ahead despite the Federal Reserve
raised the interest rates six times in the past 14 months in an
effort to slow the economy and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
Jobs in manufacturing rose by 46,000 last month after
exhibiting little growth during the first six months of this year.
Construction employment edged up by 6,000, down slightly from a
monthly average gain of 17,000 so far this year.
</P>
<P>
In services, where most Americans work, retail trade showed a
gain of 49,000 workers with restaurants and bars posting strong
job gains that helped offset the continued declines at department
stores.
</P>
<P>
The Fed next meets on August 22 and economists are divided over
whether it will feel the need to increase rates for the seventh
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
