<HEADLINE> Economic Cooperation Figures on Mori's Agenda: Bangladeshi FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Greater economic cooperation,
including increase of investment, expansion of trade and
assistance in Bangladesh's infrastructure sector, would feature
Dhaka-Tokyo talks during Japanese Prime Minister's forthcoming
visit, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad told reporters here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yoshihiro Mori, who assumed office after the death of Obuchi,
will arrive here on August 19 for a two-day official visit, on the
first leg of his three-nation South Asian tour. From Dhaka, the
prime minister will fly for New Delhi and Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Besides economic matters, other bilateral as well as regional
and international issues would come up for discussion at the talks
between Mori and host Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, Azad said,
adding that boosting cooperation between Japan and regional
organizations like the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation would also figure at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Although one of the main objectives of Mori's South Asia trip
is expected to be campaigning for expansion of the United Nations
Security Council with Japan as its new permanent member,
Bangladeshi diplomats, politicians and business leaders consider
his Dhaka visit very significant.
</P>
<P>
As an important trade partner of Bangladesh, Japan's actual
investment in the country as of August 1999 was 57.8 million U.S.
dollars in 25 units. Japan's total loan aid up to 1998 was 3.01
billion dollars and grants (grant aid and technical cooperation) 2.
8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Apart from trade and business, Japan provides scholarships for
students, teachers and government officials every year. Many
skilled and semi-skilled laborers are working in Japan. An
official source said there are some 6,422 registered Bangladeshi
people living in Japan, while the number of unrecognized workers
is likely to be double the official figure. 
</P>
