<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Short-Term Debt Continues Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's short-term foreign
debt rose to 47.5 billion U.S. dollars in June, accounting for 33.
4 percent of its total external debt of 142 billion, the Ministry
of Finance and Economy said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The short-term debt in proportion to the total foreign debt has
grown in the past six months from 27.9 percent in December to 33.4
percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The record high was registered in March 1998, exceeding 34.7
percent, while the nation was gripped by a financial crisis caused
by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The short-term debt has risen from 30 billion U.S. dollars in
February 1999 along with the nation's economic recovery from the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The country's total external debt hit 142 billion U.S. dollars
in June, up 500 million from May, but the long-term foreign debt
fell 200 million to 94.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of short-term debt to foreign reserves, an indicator
representing the nation's ability to pay external debt, was 52.7
percent, down 1.3 percent from last month's figure.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's foreign reserves stood at 91.3 billion U.S.
dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
When looking back on the fact that soaring short-term debt was
the main culprit in driving the nation into the financial crisis,
the mounting short-term debt is a worrying development, observers
said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise of the short-term debt to the
fact that South Korean companies increased their credit purchases
and overseas branches of South Korean banks increased their
borrowing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
