<HEADLINE> Lakers' West to Retire from Executive Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Jerry West, part of seven NBA
championships in four decades as a player, coach and executive
with the Lakers, will retire on Monday, but continue as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
West who won a championship with the Lakers as a player and six
more as an executive, was one of the NBA 50 Greatests for his 14
professional seasons started from 1961 when he was drafted out of
West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
He also coached the team for three seasons before moving into
the front office.
</P>
<P>
Former Lakers coach Kurt Rambis is expected to become assistant
general manager under Mitch Kupchak who is to assume most of West'
s duties, and coach Phil Jackson will have a stronger say in
roster decisions, the Los Angeles Times said.
</P>
<P>
West previously signed a four-year contract extension that runs
through the 2002-2003 season. The deal reportedly is worth 3.5
million US dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
He has repeatedly talked about leaving, most recently after the
Lakers won the NBA championship in June, citing health reasons for
an irregular heartbeat caused by nervous tension. 
