<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Sri Lankans Still Divided Over Political Solution  to Ethnic Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
News Analysis: Sri Lankans Still Divided Over Political
Solution to Ethnic Conflicts
</P>
<P>
 By Lian Guohui
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Five years ago, the Sri Lankan
government for the first time unveiled a landmark devolution
package which aims at politically ending the long-running ethnic
conflicts between majority Sinhalese dominated government troops
and separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, after five years of bargaining, conflict-ridden Sri
Lankans are still divided over a draft constitution which embodies
the devolution package, analysts here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government of ruling People's Alliance (PA) on Thursday
presented the draft constitution to the parliament amid protests
in and around Kotte, the venue of the parliament in eastern
suburban Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said a parliament member from the opposition United
National Party (UNP) burned in public one copy of the draft
constitution distributed to him. Some other UNP parliament members
tore up and crumpled the copies before throwing away. Thousands of
leftists and Buddhist monks staged a sit-down protest near
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The parliament was summoned by President Chandrika Kumaratunga
for an emergency session for the government to unveil the new
constitution that seeks to turn the country into a de facto
federal state and end the bloody ethnic war by devolving more
powers to regional councils to win over moderate minority Tamils,
sidelining the LTTE rebels, who have been fighting for a separate
homeland called Eelam for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and
east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
However, President Kumaratunga sometimes cannot make her voice
heard in a speech to present the draft constitution as the
parliament members from the opposition United National Party (UNP)
shouted her down and made lots of noises.
</P>
<P>
The UNP, which holds the balance of power to make or break
reforms, has pledged to work for peace but withdrew their support
at the last minute, claiming that the government had not given
sufficient time for the Buddhist clergy and the people to study
the provisions of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan talks between the PA and the UNP initiated in
March. However, the four-month talks failed to reach consensus on
the draft constitution with the UNP resorting to the strategy of
dragging on and beating around the bush.
</P>
<P>
Besides the UNP, the influential Buddhist clergy in this
predominantly Buddhist country has voiced strong opposition to the
government's draft constitution, arguing that it gives too many
concessions to the Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
19 million people.
</P>
<P>
They have expressed the fear that under the new constitution
Buddhism would lose its status as the dominant religion in Sri
Lanka. In Sri Lanka, Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, account
for 74 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Despite preaching nonviolence, monks have urged the government
to carry on its war against LTTE rebels as part of protecting
their religion and said the country's minority Tamils, who are
mostly Hindus, should not be given any special privileges.
</P>
<P>
"We now advise you to act as a patriotic head of state by
ceasing all negotiations immediately, crushing this cruel
terrorism without delay by the use of state power. Toward this end
you will get our blessings," Sri Lanka's top four monks had said
in a joint letter in March to President Kumaratunga, who is
herself a Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
The government is bound by the present constitution, which says
it is the duty of the state to protect and foster Buddhism. The
country's 30,000 monks could wield immense influence and they have
affected political decisions in the past.
</P>
<P>
Two key monks last month signed a letter calling on
parliamentarians to vote against the new constitution after
meeting Constitutional Affairs Minister G.L. Peiris, the
government's emissary sent to placate the monks.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga could not afford to alienate the influential
Buddhist clergy with parliamentary elections, which have to be
held by early November, around the corner.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels were banned by the Sri Lankan government in
1998 as the Buddhist clergy was enraged by a rebel suicide attack
which killed 17 people and damaged Sri Lankan Buddhists' holiest
shrine, the Temple of the Tooth, in the central hill city of Kandy.
</P>
<P>
The newly-formed nationalist Sinhala Urumaya (heritage) party
has begun to take center stage in the growing movement opposing
the reforms. The party, working hand in glove with the monks, has
been told by the National Sangha Council (Council of Monks) to "
fight for the rights of the Sinhalese" and block the new
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The government has announced the draft constitution would be
taken up for debate on August 7 and 8 and put to vote on August 9.
The government needs the votes of 150 members in the 225-seat
assembly, but the ruling party is short of at least 12 votes even
if it is able to hold all its allies together. The government will
face an uphill battle to engineer the defections of a sufficient
number of UNP lawmakers to avoid an embarrassing defeat.
</P>
<P>
In a ruling read out by Parliament Speaker K.B. Ratnayake, Sri
Lanka's Supreme Court on Thursday ordered the government to hold a
national referendum for the new draft constitution. The ruling
said that the parliament must approve the draft by a two-thirds
majority before the national referendum.
</P>
<P>
With obstacles ahead, the government also has to deal with the
intransigent LTTE rebels who have rejected the draft constitution,
claiming that they will settle for nothing less than an
independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipino Suspects Said To Be Ruled out in Jakarta Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian probers ruled out the
possibility of Filipinos being behind the Tuesday bombing attack
at the residence of Philippine Ambassador to Indonesia in Jakarta,
Vice Philippine President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine biggest TV network ABS-CBN, Arroyo
said this information was relayed by Indonesian authorities to the
Philippines' Department of Foreign Affairs after injured
Ambassador Leonides Caday himself downplayed the theory of a
Filipino being behind the attack.
</P>
<P>
The authorities reportedly said they are looking into the angle
that Indonesian militants staged the attack to embarrass the
Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, a review on the list of Filipinos who were in
Indonesia for the past six months will continue.
</P>
<P>
Also, a plan to send a Philippine investigating team to Jakarta
to help in the probe will push through, Philippine officials said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which took lace in front of the Philippine
Ambassador's residence in central Jakarta at 12:25 p.m. on Tuesday,
killed two people and injured 21 others including the Philippine
envoy.
</P>
<P>
Caday, who fractured both his thighs, was reportedly in a
stable condition on Wednesday, recovering from surgery after being
seriously injured by the massive blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
