<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Electronic Exports May Top 60 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's electronic exports
are expected to top 60 billion U.S. dollars this year, an increase
of 10 billion over 1999, the country's Commerce, Industry and
Energy Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The estimate is based on the results of the first half of this
year, which show the country's electronic exports rose to 32.1
billion dollars, up 34.8 percent from the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The industry ministry said the upward trend, if not broken,
would bring this year's electronic export total up to more than 60
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has seen a continuous growth in the export of its
electronic products, which increased to 40 billion dollars in 1995
from 20 billion in 1991 and 10 billion in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Last year, electronic exports accounted for 37 percent of the
country's total, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Semiconductors represented 37.1 percent, LCD 7.9 percent, and
mobile phones 7.7 percent of South Korea's electronic exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, 53.9 percent of the electronic
exports went to the United States, the European Union member
countries and Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
