<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Airlines (THY) has started a bidding process
for a contract to purchase 8,000 pillows stuffed with chick down,
reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The down will come from chicks no older than 45 days, according
to a THY announcement earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The material for the covers should be pure cotton with top
quality threads and stitching to prevent loss of feathers.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Investments in the Israeli industry continued to
rise in the first half of the year, but at a much slower pace of 5-
10 percent as compared to a 29 percent hike in the same period of
last year, according to the Israeli Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
Despite that, real investments rose by 27 percent in the first
quarter of 2000, amounting to 3.3 billion shekels (about 800
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The hi-tech sector accounted for 84 percent of the total
investment growth, as investments in advanced technology companies
surged 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The famous U.S. beer Miller Genuine Draft was
introduced into Turkey on Thursday following the finalization of a
licensing agreement with Turkish brewer Efes of the Anadolu Group,
reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Miller Genuine Draft will be sold only in big cities and tourist
resorts in Turkey and will be distributed by Efes.
</P>
<P>
Miller Brewing Company, a subsidiary of Philip Morris and
founded in 1855, is one of the largest brewers in the world, with
5.3 billion liters of beer sold last year. Based in Milwaukee,
Wisconsin, the company sells its products in more than 100
countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Efes, which leads the Turkish beer market with 80 percent market
share, is said to be the largest beer producer in the Eurasia zone
between the Adriatic Sea and China.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Transport Ibrahim el-Demiri said
his ministry has received three tenders from foreign firms to
upgrade the Damietta Port and raise its capacity to receive 1.2
million containers annually.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry will not review the proposals until it can
coordinate with the Ministry of Public Enterprise to allow national
companies an opportunity to submit their tenders, The Egyptian
Gazette newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The port upgrades include construction of new docks and
restoration of existing ones, and construction of facilities to
attract international shipping companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
