<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Researchers Invent New Method of Gold Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Romanian researchers have
invented an ecologically-friendly method to recover gold from
various compositions or tailings, a local newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The invention, called Hydrometallurgical Gold Recovery, is the
result of teamwork among researchers headed by Rozalia Radulescu
and Filip Gheorghe, at the Institute for Rare Metals, which is
located in Bucharest, the Curentul daily newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The method, free of cyanide or mercury ions, recoups the gold
from various compositions or tailings, and can be applied to waste
resulting from ores and pyrite drosses at sulfur acid mills.
</P>
<P>
Unlike classical methods, which provide about 70-80 percent of
gold recovery, this invention has a gold recovery yield rate of 97
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Land Price Falls For Eighth Straight Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The average price of land in Japan
as of January 1 dropped 7 percent from the previous year for the
eighth consecutive year, the National Tax Administration Agency
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The average land price, based on data on 400,000 privately held
plots facing main roads and streets across Japan, fell to 146,000
yen (about 1,348 dollars) per square meter, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Land prices declined in all 47 prefectures except Shimane
Prefecture, where the average land price remained flat.
</P>
<P>
Chiba Prefecture had the largest rate of decline of 11.9
percent, followed by Osaka Prefecture's 10.9 percent, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
In the Tokyo area, which is formed by the central areas of
Tokyo, Chiba, Kanagawa and Saitama prefectures, the year-on-year
decline rate was 7.2 percent, down from 7.6 percent in the
previous year. The figure for the Nagoya region, comprising
central Aichi Prefecture and part of Mie Prefecture, declined from
8.8 percent to 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In key locations across the country, the average price in
residential areas fell 3.6 percent from a year earlier to 107,000
yen (987.9 dollars), while the average price in commercial areas
and industrial areas dropped by 12 percent and 6.2 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The continued decline of land prices shows that Japan's economy
is still struggling to overcome the effects of the collapse of the
asset-inflated bubble economy of the late 1980s, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
