<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Organizers Ready to Tune Up for Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Despite an 18-month distance,
the organizers for the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City said
Friday that they're ready to fine-tune plans for everything.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake Organizing Committee will stage 17 test events
from October to March, just weeks after the Summer Olympics in
Australia, with competition ranged from figure skating to ski
jumping.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, events will be staged simultaneously at
different venues, designed to simulate the steady pace of the
Olympics, which run from February 8-24, 2002.
</P>
<P>
"We want our staff and volunteers to get a close sense of what
it feels like to have several events going on at the same time,"
said Cathy Priestner-Allinger, SLOC's managing director of sports.
</P>
<P>
The first test event, a short-track speedskating World Cup meet
at The Peaks Ice Arena in Provo, will take place on October 27,
just 26 days after the Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee has approved its 78-event
schedule for the largest Winter Games ever.
</P>
<P>
This winter, Utah venues will host competitions of biathlon,
curling, speedskating, figure skating, ice hockey, slalom and
downhill skiing, Nordic skiing, freestyle skiing, ski jumping,
snowboard, bobsled, luge and skeleton.
</P>
<P>
Among the venues opening next winter are the ski jumps, the
speedskating oval and a hockey practice rink. 
</P>
</TEXT>
