<HEADLINE> Michael Johnson Backs to Training After Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Three-time Olympic gold
medalist Michael Johnson is back to training for the first time
since suffering a hamstring injury at the U.S. Olympic Track and
Field Trials last month.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who walked away after some 80 meters in the 200-meter
finals at the trials, will run the 400 meters and 4x400 relay in
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"I started back training this week after taking off all of last
week with a sore hamstring," Johnson said in a letter to fans
posted on his web site.
</P>
<P>
"After all of the swelling went down, we determined that the
cramp I suffered in the 200 final at the trials had actually
caused a slight strain in my hamstring."
</P>
<P>
"My Achilles, hamstring, and the quadriceps that cramped in the
preliminaries of the 200 at the trials are all still sore as a
result of all the cramping."
</P>
<P>
But while the soreness has caused Johnson some discomfort, he
said he would be completely recovered in time for the Olympic
Games in September.
</P>
<P>
"I'm fortunate that my injuries were not major or season-ending.
I will be fully prepared to go into the Olympics and defend my
title in the 400 meters -- and become the first man to do so."
</P>
<P>
As far as his competition schedule leading up to the Olympics,
Johnson canceled an appearance scheduled for this weekend in
Sweden and is undecided about a meet next week in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He has reiterated that he will only be running 400s for the
remainder of the year and has not thought about his race plans
beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
Johnson also made it clear that there is no way he will be
running the 200 in Sydney. "I will not be appealing to the Olympic
Committee for any special treatment or exemption into the 200 at
the Olympics. I would not accept any type of exemption if it was
offered to me." 
</P>
</TEXT>
