<HEADLINE> Magic Lead Frenzy of NBA Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Orlando Magic, who were 20
million under the salary cap, as expected have spent the most on
free agents since the NBA signing frenzy began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Magic have spent about 200 million US dollars, which will
be spread over the next seven years, to lure Grant Hill away from
Detroit and Tracy McGrady and Dee Brown from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The Magic signed both Hill and McGrady to seven-year 93-million
US dollars deals, the maximum they were eligible to receive, after
engineering sign-and-trade deals. Brown signed a one-year 1-
million deal.
</P>
<P>
"All of this is gratifying, but we're not finished," said Magic
coach Doc Rivers, "Now we've got to go out and win."
</P>
<P>
Orlando was 41-41 last season and missed the playoffs by one
game. General manager John Gabriel called it a relaunching season
after he gutted the roster by trading several high-salaried
players to clear room under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
The Indiana Pacers, who were over the 35.5 million per team
salary cap, have also emerged as big spenders, spending 146.25
million dollars over seven years to re-sign swingman Jalen Rose,
Austin Croshere and Sam Perkins.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers aren't done spending. Indian president Donnie Walsh
is negotiating to re-sign guards Reggie Miller and Mark Jackson
and center Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
Miami, which will pay All-Star guard Eddie Jones 86.5 million
dollars over seven years after obtaining him in a nine-player sign-
and-trade deal with the Charlotte Hornets, are next on the list of
spenders.
</P>
<P>
Miami is followed by the Milwaukee Bucks, 67 million dollars on
re-signing Tim Thomas, and the San Antonio Spurs, 63.4 million on
re-signing Tim Duncan, Antonio Daniels and Avery Johnson. 
</P>
