<HEADLINE> Four Nobel Laureates in China Attending Academic Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Four Nobel Prize laureates and a
noted mathematician gathered here today for a three-day academic
exchange with Chinese researchers at the invitation of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
They are Chen Ning Yang, Samuel C.C. Ting, laureates of the
Nobel Prize for Physics, Rudolph Marcus, an American scientist who
was awarded the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1992, Hartmut Michel,
a German who won the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1988, and Shing-
Tung Yau, an American mathematician.
</P>
<P>
Yau was given the Fields Prize in 1983, the highest honor in
mathematics. Both Professor Yau and Professor Marcus gave a
lecture today on mathematics research and the ozone layer at CAS
attended by hundreds of Chinese researchers. Professor Yang and
Professor Michel are scheduled to make separate presentations on
culture in science and gene research on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During a discussion today with leaders of CAS, the four Nobel
laureates offered suggestions on the restructuring of CAS and a
knowledge-based innovation plan initiated in 1998 by CAS to become
a world-class research institution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
