<HEADLINE> Arafat Due in Turkey on Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
will arrive in Turkey on Saturday to update Turkish leaders on the
latest developments of the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to meet with Turkish President Ahmet Necdet
Sezer, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
during his brief visit, Anatolia News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S.-brokered peace talks between Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak failed at Camp David last month, the
Palestinian leader has embarked on a long journey to seek
international support for the justified Palestinian position on the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will brief Turkish leaders on his steadfast stance on
declaring an independent Palestinian state on September 13 no
matter whether there is a peace agreement with Israel or not.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is currently on a visit to South Africa. He has visited
Egypt, France, Saudi Arabia, Yemen, Morocco, Tunisia and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Turkey believes it is a major power which has all kinds of
vested interests in the region, said the report. The Ottoman Turks
ruled over Jerusalem, as well as the rest of the Middle East, for
400 years until the early years of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was one of the first Muslim countries to recognize Israel
in 1948, but lowered its level of diplomatic representation to
charge d'affaires in Tel Aviv in 1981 when Israel declared
Jerusalem as its "eternal" capital. Ankara also closed its
consulate-general in Arab East Jerusalem as well.
</P>
<P>
As the Middle East peace process was launched in Madrid in 1991,
Turkey reciprocally upgraded its diplomatic relations with Israel
to the level of ambassador. At the same time, the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO) Office in Ankara was turned into an
embassy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
