<HEADLINE> Pakistanis Generally Feel Hard Work Rarely Pays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A majority of the people in
Pakistan do not attribute wealth to hard work or education and
instead believe that wealth comes out of "inheritance, ill-gotten
money or sheer luck", Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a recent survey by Gallup Pakistan, the report said
that some people attribute it to an opportunity to work abroad.
Following the same argument, a majority do not attribute poverty
to laziness or lack of devotion to work and instead attribute this
phenomenon to birth in a poor family, fate and abstention from
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among nearly 1500 men an women
statistically selected from the rural and urban areas of all the
four provinces, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20 percent attributed wealth to hard work and six
percent to good education but the majority (30 percent) attributed
it to birth in a rich family. As many as 22 percent were of the
view that it comes through ill-gotten money and 12 percent
believed that the luck or fate has a role, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
