<HEADLINE> Experts Urge to Stop New Cable Car Project at Taishan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Some well-known Chinese heritage
experts recently urged the immediate stop on the expansion of
cable-car project on Mount Taishan, one of China's five most
famous mountain resorts.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen experts, including Hou Renzhi, an academician from the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), Wu Liangyong, an academician
from the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE), Xie Ninggao,
heritage professor from Beijing University, and Luo Zhewen, an
expert on ancient architecture with the State Administration of
Cultural Heritage (SACH), suggest pulling down existing cable-car
facilities and replant trees and vegetation on the peak to protect
the world-famous cultural site, according to today's "Guangming
Daily".
</P>
<P>
The cable car, linking the peak and Zhongtian Gate, is long due
for servicing. It has been operating for some twenty years.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that the expansion planned by local
authorities will further destroy the environment and view of the
majestic mountain.
</P>
<P>
Taishan is located in Tai'an City in Shandong Province and is 1,
545-meters high. In 1987, Mount Taishan was added to the list of
World Heritage sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Establish Journalists' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese journalists will have
their own festival -- "Journalists' Day" on November 8 if a
relevant proposal is approved, according to a report in the China
Youth Daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the proposal for establishment of the festival is
being considered by the Legislative Affairs Bureau of the State
Council, and will be promulgated after going through the
legislative procedures.
</P>
<P>
The Journalists' Day will be a work-as-usual holiday for
journalists, just like the country's Teachers' Day and Nurses' Day,
when teachers and nurses have to work on their posts.
</P>
<P>
The date was chosen because on November 8, 1937 the China Young
Journalists Association was founded by left-wing reporters headed
by Fan Changjiang in the city of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Journalists' Day will encourage all
Chinese journalists to carry forward the fine traditions and do
their best for the just cause, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Journalists Association is expected to hold
various activities to mark the new festival, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
