<HEADLINE> Chinese-Improved Linux to be Installed in PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese PC producer TCL is going
to install a Red Flag Linux operating system in its personal
computers, a move to break the monopoly of Microsoft's Windows
operating system in the booming Chinese PC market.
</P>
<P>
Liu Bo, chief executive officer of Red Flag Software Co. and
Zhu Xuefeng, vice-general manager of TCL, signed an agreement here
today on the installation of the operating system, known as Red
Flag Linux Desktop 2.0.
</P>
<P>
TCL ranks sixth among China's PC industry.
</P>
<P>
Yang Li, a spokeswoman for Red Flag Software Co., said the
Linux-based Desktop 2.0 has already passed the tests of mainstream
PC producers, including IBM, HP, Compaq and Chinese PC producer
the Great Wall Computer Co.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the success of the Red Flag operating system will
see the monopoly of Microsoft's Windows operating system reduced.
</P>
<P>
The Linux operating system, widely believed safer and use-
friendly than Windows, is enjoying growing market shares around
the world. 
</P>
