<HEADLINE> Dummy Missile Crashed Car in Darwin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, the missile was
dropped from a training FA-18 Hornet of the Australian Air Force
around 9 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the air force Darwin confirmed that "a
training device" had been lost from the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The jet was returning from a night sortie as part of an
Operation Pitch Black, which was an annual multinational air
defense exercise based in Northern Australia and involving British
and Singaporean troops.
</P>
<P>
The two-metre long and 130-kg missile crashed a Land Cruiser
parked in a car repair yard in a industrial suburb of Darwin and
totally destroyed it.
</P>
<P>
No body was killed or injured in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials were investigating the incident. All similar
devices have been removed from FA-18 Hornets involved in the
exercise as a safety precaution.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister John Moore said there were no plans to halt
the training flights. 
</P>
