<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Steps Up Search for Foreign Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We are continuously working hard to explore international
labor market through the mobilization of Royal Nepalese embassies,
" Kumar Joshi, chief at Foreign Employment Section of Labor
Ministry, told the press.
</P>
<P>
The government will soon finalize the process of sending
Nepalese workers to Israel to work as agriculture laborers, said
Joshi.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government will also send 14 government employees
to work in the Arab International Agriculture Center under an
internship program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is studying the prospect for
exporting manpower to a number of other countries from which
Nepal's manpower agencies have received demand, including Cyprus,
Germany, the Netherlands, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics show that during the fiscal year of 1999-
2000 ending on July 15, altogether 8,192 people went abroad for
job through registered manpower agencies while 15,208 people did
so on the basis of their own contacts. The total figure is 20
percent higher than that of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign employment is a major source of foreign exchanges for
Nepal. Unofficial estimates put the total number of Nepalese
workers working abroad at 350,000, who sent home up to 990 million
U.S. dollars in 1996-1997 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
