<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN-sponsored Vehicle Regulations Agreement to Take Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The international agreement on
global vehicle regulations will become effective on 25 August 2000,
to which eight countries and regional organizations have become
contracting parties, said a press release jointly issued by the
United Nations and Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Federation became the eighth contracting party on
July 26 when V. S. Sidorov, permanent representative of the
federation to the U.N. and other international organizations in
Geneva, signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The other seven contracting parties are Canada, France, Germany,
Japan, the United Kingdom, the United States and the European
Community.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was concluded in Geneva in 1998 in the
framework of the UN/ECE Working Party on the Construction of
Vehicles after three years of intense negotiations, provides the
legal framework for the formulation of global automotive
regulations to improve the safety, environmental protection,
energy efficiency and anti-theft performance of road vehicles, and
to reduce manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
The international regulations will be made by mainly
harmonizing the existing national regulations.
</P>
<P>
Several other countries, including South Africa and Spain, have
expressed their intention to become parties to the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
