<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of China's T-Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China's T-bond market went
bullish this week, led by the three bonds listed after 1999, all
of which hit record highs with expanded turnover, according to
Homeway, a leading online financial and securities advisory firm.
</P>
<P>
009905 (3.2 percent, due 2007), 009908(3.3 percent, due 2009)
and 010004, a newly listed bond with the coupon rate floating 0.62
percentage points above the interest rate of one-year time
deposits at banks, grew 0.31 yuan, 0.34 yuan and 0.91 yuan to
create new highs of 102.71 yuan, 102.48 yuan and 103.49 yuan,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
As this year's interest payments of the first two are
approaching, they witnessed apparent expansions in the trade
volume, indicating active capital inflow.
</P>
<P>
Bond 009704 (9.78 percent , due 2007) rose 0.80 yuan to 144.90
yuan by its good intrinsic yield at 2.88 percent, the highest
among all current bonds. 000696 (11.83 percent, due 2006) and
000896 (8.56 percent, due 2003) saw rises of 0.04 yuan and 0.21
yuan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The gain this week reflected ample capital supply. As the A-
share stock market has kept bullish for seven straight months,
potential corrections pose mounting risks to investors. Thus more
and more capital might be thrown into the fixed income treasury
market to drive up T-bonds.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the future operations of open-ended fund and Sino-
foreign co-operative funds are also expected to help revive
treasuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
