<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Asks Militant Groups to Come Forward For Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The current dialogue between the Indian central government and
Hizbul Mujahideen, a major militant outfit in Kashmir, was part of
the peace efforts, Vajpayee said while making a statement in the
Lok Sabha, or the Indian parliament, here on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
"Other (militant) groups which have chosen the path of violence
should also realize that the people of Jammu and Kashmir want
peace...It is futile for them to continue on the path of violence,
" Vajpayee was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
These militant groups should come forward for talks with the
government for redress of their grievances, he added.
</P>
<P>
"I may add that while the fight against terrorism will continue,
India will not give up efforts for restoration of peace in Jammu
and Kashmir," stressed the prime minister, who on Thursday paid a
day's visit to Kashmir where a series of militant attacks against
civilians on August 1 evening killed at least 100 people and
injured nearly 100 others.
</P>
<P>
The perpetrators of the massacres were obviously trying to
sabotage the recent peace initiative by the Indian government and
Hizbul Mujahideen, which reached a ceasefire last week and started
talks in Kashmir on Thursday for the first time in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report of the PTI, U.S. Ambassador to India
Richard F Celeste said here on Friday that his country "fully
supports" India's attempt for dialogue in Kashmir and hopes that
the dialogue would be successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Asked to Speed Up BIMP-EAGA Project Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ministers from all the four member countries expressed their
concern over the lack in progress in the implementation of
projects for BIMP-EAGA at their three-day meeting which ended in
Labuan, off Sabah, East Malaysia, Friday, Malaysian Finance
Minister Daim Zainuddin who chaired the meeting said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that the private sector must use the East
ASEAN Business Council (EABC) to sort out whatever problems they
face implementing projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there were various memoranda of understanding (MoUs)
signed among BIMP-EAGA members but many delayed the implementation
of the projects.
</P>
<P>
"The reason given (for the delay) was the economic recession.
But now, we hope that with the economic recovery, they can move on,
" Bernama quoted Daim as saying in Labuan.
</P>
<P>
The private sector must be aggressive in seizing opportunities
to undertake projects which were viable and beneficial to all
economies, he said, adding the government is only playing the role
of a facilitator in such matters.
</P>
<P>
The minister asked the private sector to use the public sector
to accelerate the pace of implementation, given the latter's
obvious advantage in facilitating the process administratively,
legally and across borders.
</P>
<P>
Daim regretted that although the grouping had been in existence
for more than six and half years, it had yet to yield the level of
dynamic growth that had been initially anticipated.
</P>
<P>
He said the less impressive performance may have been partly
due to the economic recession but it is timely for now that member
countries review the BIMP-EAGA process.
</P>
<P>
Daim said the meeting agreed that states would be given more
powers to make decisions to expedite investments implemented in
their territories.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Brunei's delegation was headed by its Industry
and Primary Resources Minister Pehin Datuk Abdul Rahman Taib,
Indonesia was represented by its Forestry and Estate Crops
Minister Nur Mahmudi Isma'il while Undersecretary for Industry and
Investments Raul C.Hernandez represented the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
