<HEADLINE> Russia Says 21 Arab Mercenaries Killed in Chechnya Updates with Kremlin spokesman office confirmation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one Arab mercenaries were
killed in a latest operation by Russian troops in the rebel
republic of Chechnya, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A group of Arab mercenaries headed by Abdul Zurka, trying to
break across the Russian-Georgian border in Chechnya's Sharoi
region to escape the battered republic, rushed into an ambush
planned by Russian federal units and were destroyed, said Sergei
Artemov, head of the press center of Russia's combined forces in
the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
After a fierce fighting, the rebels left 21 bodies at the scene
and their head Zurka was captured with heavy wounds, Tass quoted
Artemov as saying, not giving the time of the battle.
</P>
<P>
Identification documents show the deceased mercenaries were
from Yemen, Morocco and other Arab states, according to the press
center.
</P>
<P>
The office of Kremlin spokesman for Chechnya Sergei
Yastrzhembsky confirmed on Friday the reported routing of the
group of foreign mercenaries in the Sharoi district of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty-one mercenaries were killed and several more captured,
among them the group's commander Abdul Salam Zurka, and the
federal intelligence formations that discovered and wiped out the
mercenary group incurred no losses," said the office, adding that
the other details of the operation are being clarified. 
</P>
