<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Calls for More Courtesy in Politicians' Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Moshe Katsav
has called on Knesset (Parliament) members (MKs) to tone down their
rhetoric and "treat each other with more respect," a local daily
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli society has not learnt the right lessons from the
assassination of former prime minister Yitzhak Rabin in 1995, said
Katsav, who was sworn in Tuesday as the country's eighth president.
</P>
<P>
Katsav made the appeal in an interview on Thursday with The
Jerusalem Post, a day after some particularly fiery exchanges were
reported from the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
In his second day at Beit Hanassi, the presidential residence,
Katsav said that during his seven-year term of office, he will try
to tone down the rhetoric in the national political dialogue, so
that different political fractions will treat each other with more
respect.
</P>
<P>
He said he is "worried that none of the sectors of society has
properly learnt the lessons of the Rabin assassination."
</P>
<P>
The new president, said the paper, had issued a similar warning
in his inaugural speech on Tuesday, to apparently little effect.
</P>
<P>
"The politicians' behavior influences the public," Katsav told
the paper. "If we want to be good leaders, we must remember to be
careful in our speech."
</P>
<P>
The president, who was named the most sportsmanlike MK in 1982,
said he will also begin a series of visits next week to different
areas of the country in an effort to promote unity. The first stop
will be Jerusalem and will be led by Mayor Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question whether he will call on Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to form a national unity government, Katsav reiterated
his desire to avoid politics. He has repeatedly pledged to steer
clear of politics.
</P>
<P>
"I have to stand above political issues, because I was elected
by MKs belonging to all the sectors - leftist and rightist, Jews
and non-Jews, Sephardim and Ashkenazim," said Katsav, an Iran-born
Sephardi.
</P>
<P>
Katsav is also the first Likud candidate to win a presidential
election, breaking into one of the final institutions that was
considered reserved for the country's elite Ashkenazi Labor Party
ruling class.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old president, whose post is largely a ceremonial
one, said, "I believe the job of the president is to form the
national and public agenda of Israeli society and I have no
intention to publicly criticize the prime minister."
</P>
<P>
Barak, whose government has been reduced to a crippling minority
one holding only 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset with the
resignations of ruling partners, has vowed to reshuffle the
government in the next few weeks. There have also been calls for
him to form a national unity government with the opposition Likud
faction.
</P>
<P>
Katsav was elected president in a secret ballot by the Knesset
on Monday, beating the leading Labor candidate, a long-time
statesman and Minister of Regional Cooperation Shimon Peres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
