<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Capital, Limiting Factor in New Economy: Singapore Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing a scholarship award ceremony Friday held by the
Economic Development Board (EDB), Minister of State for Trade &AMP;
Industry and Communications &AMP; Information Technology Lim Swee Say
said that the limiting factor for Singapore in the New Economy and
Information Society is human capital.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that this means that Singapore will increasingly
be competing in the world for human capital and with human capital.
</P>
<P>
After listing Singapore's major achievements in the 35 years
since its independence in 1965, Lim said that his country will
face new challenges and threats of structural unemployment,
widening income gap and digital divide in the new age of New
Economy and Information Society.
</P>
<P>
He said, "For 35 years, we competed with the world for jobs,
technology, markets and capital because these were the leading
contributing factors to economic growth and social progress."
</P>
<P>
"However, in the new world of technology and globalization,
technology, infrastructure and even financial capital will no
longer be the limiting factor of economic growth and social
progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To remain competitive and cohesive as we continue the journey
of nation building, our key challenge is to be able to further
strengthen our human capital to the best of our ability," he
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
