<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- Kazakhstan is in negotiations with American and
European countries, particularly the United States and Britain, on
the capture of former Kazakh Prime Minister Akezhan Kazhegeldin
and his extradition to Kazakhstan to face trial on criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
Competent Kazakh authorities have opened a criminal case
against the former prime minister, who resigned in 1997 and is now
opposition leader of Kazakhstan. The Interfax news agency quoted
Kazakh Procurator General Yuri Khitri as saying on Thursday that
Kazhegeldin is charged with taking bribes, illegal amassing of
property, abuse of power, illegal possession and transfer of
weapons and tax evasion. He is also under investigation for
dereliction of duty. An international warrant has been issued for
his capture for criminal investigations. (Kazakhstan-Former
Premier-Corruption)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- A new poll result showed that about 67 percent
Austrians opposed holding a referendum to force the other 14 EU
states to lift political sanctions against the country, the
Austria Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Only 25 percent people inquired welcomed the referendum
scheduled for this autumn, while more than 60 percent considered
the plan as "an absolute nonsense". The referendum plan was
approved by Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel and far-rightist Joerg
Haider in early July, after other EU governments froze political
contacts with Austria because of Haider's Freedom Party's entry
into the government in February. ( Austria-Poll-Referendum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank Thursday urged the Bosnian Serb authorities to take swift
action to improve the republic's flagging economy, otherwise
future economic assistance from international financial
institutions could be affected.
</P>
<P>
Bruno De Sacen, IMF representative in Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Thursday said in Banja Luka that the budget deficit of the Serbs'
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegoniva may have reached up to about 200
million German marks (90 million U.S. dollars). To solve the
imbalance, the Serb government must take actions against
peculation and graft and also fight against rampant smuggling,
Bruno advised. (Bosnia-Serbs-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA -- Texas Governor George W. Bush accepted U.S.
Republican nomination for presidential candidate at the party's
National Convention here Thursday, vowing to "change the tone of
Washington to one of civility and respect."
</P>
<P>
In his acceptance speech meant to run against Vice President Al
Gore for the White House, Bush told Republican delegates that he
would work to forge agreement on problems long stuck in
partisanship. "We will confront the hard issues, threats to our
national security, threats to our health and retirement security,
before the challenges of our time become crises for our children,"
he said. (U.S.-Bush-Nomination-Acceptance) 
</P>
