<HEADLINE> S. Korean Electronic Export Expected to Hit 60 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korean export of electronic
products is expected to reach 60 billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
The country's electronic goods export totaled 32.1 billion U.S.
dollars in the first half of this year, up 34.8 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce, Industry and Energy Ministry Friday said if the
trend continues, the country will export over 60 billion U.S.
dollars worth of electronic goods this year.
</P>
<P>
South Korean electronic goods export amounted to 10 billion U.S.
dollars in 1987, 20 billion in 1991, 30 billion in 1994, 40
billion in 1995 and 50 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The electronic product export accounted for 37 percent of the
country's total exports last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the electronic goods exported, semiconductors accounted for
37.1 percent, LCD 7.9 percent, mobile phones 7.7 percent, cathode
ray tubes 5.5 percent, monitors 5.3 percent, personal computers 4.
0 percent, fiber optic disk drives 2.3 percent, air conditioners 1.
7 percent, color TVs 1.4 percent and VCRs 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 53.9 percent of the electric product export went to the
United States, the European Union and Japan while the rest went to
China and other countries or regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
