<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Executive Committee Supports World Cup Rotation Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The FIFA Executive Committee has
expressed a clear opinion in favor of some form of rotating the
FIFA World Cup among the six continental confederations, as from
the year 2010, according to a FIFA press release received here
today.
</P>
<P>
The Committee, meeting Thursday in Zurich under the
chairmanship of the FIFA President, Joseph S. Blatter, unanimously
backed Blatter's suggestion to ensure that all continents be given
an equal opportunity to host the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The issue will now go to the FIFA Strategic Study Committee,
which includes the presidents and general secretaries of the six
confederations as well as the FIFA President, the Senior Vice-
President and the General Secretary, to elaborate further details
of this basic principle.
</P>
<P>
President Blatter also informed the committee of developments
since the same committee decided on July 6 to designate Germany as
host nation of the FIFA World Cup in 2006. He reiterated that the
decision was taken in conformity with all regulations, and was
final. He also added that the initiative taken by the defeated
South African Football Association to take the matter to
arbitration was inappropriate, and not supported by the African
Football Confederation (CAF).
</P>
<P>
The committee confirmed that the second edition of the FIFA
Club World Championship would be held in Spain in summer 2001,
with 12 teams taking part. The FIFA Organizing Committee will
work out the criteria to determine these teams.
</P>
<P>
It is planned to hold the FIFA Confederations Cup in 2001
jointly in Korea and Japan, as a test event for the first co-
hosted World Cup a year later. The eight teams will include the
two host countries, France Brazil, Cameroon, Canada and Australia
as their respective continental champions, and Mexico as the cup-
holders. Dates for the event have yet to be finalized, but are
expected to be in June.
</P>
<P>
A decision on the venue for the 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup,
for which Australia and China are candidates, will be taken in
conjunction with a decision on the first World Women's Under-18
Championship, planned for 2002.
</P>
<P>
The special arrangement by which the Auckland Kingz club team
from New Zealand is permitted to play in the National Soccer
League in Australia was prolonged from the current two years to
five years. The Committee stressed however that this was a special
dispensation and was not intended to set a new trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
