<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is expected to give top
priority to forming a new coalition with Meretz and Shas parties, a
One Israel source said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said Barak believes he can overcome the differences between
the two parties that led to the June coalition crisis that resulted
in the resignation of three Meretz ministers. Meretz has remained
in the coalition. Shas pulled out of the cabinet and the coalition
last month after Barak decided to go to the Camp David peace
summit.
</P>
<P>
Barak's options are limited since he plans to pursue a framework
agreement with the Palestinians, the source said. He has recently
met with Meretz leader Yossi Sarid and Shas leader Eli Yishai, and
both expressed frustration over the past, but did not rule out a
new partnership.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak met in Alexandria, Egypt Thursday for talks on the
peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians and to
discuss the results of the Camp David summit. The two leaders met
privately and then had a lunch meeting in which their aides took
part.
</P>
<P>
The trip to Alexandria was Barak's first outside Israel since
his return home from the United States last week.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Barak told Israeli reporters during a
separate press conference that he believes the Egyptian president
understands the difficulties and complexities of the problems
facing the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat arrived unexpectedly in
South Africa Thursday to ask former president Nelson Mandela to
help revive the peace talks. Mandela had managed to advise Arafat
last year to shelve his planned unilateral declaration of a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in South Africa, Arafat said he believes U.S.
President Bill Clinton can help the Palestinians and Israelis
resolve their two major remaining differences, which are the status
of Jerusalem and the right of Palestinian refugees to return home
or receive compensation.
</P>
<P>
"If we solve these two problems, we feel it is still possible to
reach an agreement before the 13th of September," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Officials in the Israeli prime minister's office reacted in
anger Thursday to reports that senior Labor party members plan to
challenge Ehud Barak for party leadership. According to the
reports, initial steps are already being taken to choose one
agreed-upon candidate to run against Barak in order not to split
the vote among his opponents.
</P>
<P>
The officials pointed an accusing finger at Knesset (Parliament)
Speaker Avraham Burg, who they said is constantly undermining the
prime minister's position.
</P>
<P>
Burg told Tel Aviv's Non Stop Radio that if a peace agreement
with the Palestinians is not reached and the elections are
advanced, "there is a high probability of a race for the party
leadership. Whether or not I am a candidate is less relevant."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami announced
Thursday that he will not challenge Barak for the party leadership
even if the peace process fails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
