<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Sturgeon Spotted in Qiantang River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Fishermen have caught a tail of
Chinese sturgeon, a rare variety of fish, at the mouth of the
Qiantang River in east China.
</P>
<P>
Elder fishermen said they can hardly find any Chinese sturgeon
in the river since the Xinanjiang Reservoir was built in the
northern part of the coastal province in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir has changed the temperature of water in the river,
which is not suitable for the fish to live in.
</P>
<P>
The 30-centimeter-long fish, with black spots on its back, is a
young Chinese sturgeon. It was caught late July but released three
days later.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jianrong, the fisherman who caught the fish, did not know
what fish it was until experts from Zhejiang Provincial Nature
Museum determined its identity.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon, on the verge of extinction, is on the
state's first-class protection list.
</P>
<P>
Referred to as a kind of "living fossils," the fish is highly
valuable for scientific research on geology, ocean and ecology.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon, the largest fish in the sturgeon family,
is peculiar to China.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese sturgeons has decreased drastically in
recent years due to river pollution, a busier navigation, illegal
fishing and building of dams.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken steps to protect Chinese sturgeons
over the past two decades. During 1983 and 1998, millions of fries
were put into the Yangtze River for breeding.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has banned the fishing of Chinese
sturgeons and controlled pollution to protect the fish, one of the
oldest vertebrates on earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-cancer Drugs Expected to Be Developed from Shark Cartilage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully extracted from shark cartilage two angiogenesis
inhibitory factors, which are likely to be turned into anticancer
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The two factors, named SCAIF (Shark Cartilage Angiogenesis
Inhibitory factor)-I and SCAIF-II, were obtained by a group of
researchers from Shanghai's Fudan University and the Shanghai
Institute of Naval Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe that the development of tumor depends on
newly emerging blood vessels and that inhibiting the growth of
blood vessels results in withering tumor.
</P>
<P>
Finding angiogenesis inhibitory factors and deriving effective
anticancer drugs from them have therefore become a key research
project in the world in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Medical experiments indicate the two newly obtained factors
remarkably prevented the growth of vessels and tumor in mice.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said their experiments have shown no harmful
side effects or toxicity in the lab.
</P>
<P>
SCAIF-I has been confirmed as a new type of protein and a
patent has been granted for its discovery.
</P>
<P>
The researchers are now engaged in cloning the factor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of major science stories released by Xinhua in the past week:
</P>
<P>
China Launches Plan to Search For Risky Earthward Objects
</P>
<P>
Chinese astronomers have planned to build a monitoring station
to search for risky earthward minor planets and comets that might
collide with the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jiexing, an astronomer in charge of the project, said the
station will be built in Tieshanshi State Forest Park in Xuyi
County in Jiangsu Province, east China, at an estimated expense of
more than 10 million yuan (1.25 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the searching plan is the necessary step before any
measures could be taken to prevent any possible disastrous
collision between the Earth and minor planets and Comets.
</P>
<P>
National High-Tech Program Open To Overseas Scientists
</P>
<P>
China is to open part of national high-tech development
programs, major basic scientific research programs and several
other State-level scientific development programs for overseas
research organs and scientists.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Ministry of Science and Technology
said that his ministry will choose a large group of civil projects
from the national scientific development programs.
</P>
<P>
Plagues Closely Related to Calcium, Iron-Rich Areas: Experts
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say they have discovered that the source of
plagues usually contain high levels of calcium and iron, a
discovery which they say will help prevent and control the
epidemic globally.
</P>
<P>
Tan Jian'an, a research fellow with the Geographic Science and
Resources Institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said
the calcium and iron-rich areas are semi-arid desert grassland in
tropical areas and temperate zones, semi-wet grassland (including
grassland in high and cold areas), and some wet and hot coastal
forests.
</P>
<P>
Artificial Weather Tech System to Be Built in Western China
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government plans to set up a modern technological
system to produce artificial weather in the western region which
has experienced frequent droughts and other kinds of natural
calamities.
</P>
<P>
The artificial weather system, composed of advanced equipment
including aircraft and ground supportive facilities will be used
to increase water for local reservoirs, increase rainfall, and
combat forest fires.
</P>
<P>
CAS Sets Up Plant Research Institute In Shanghai
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences set up an institute in Shanghai
on August 1 to develop and promote research work on the physiology,
plant ecology and the application of modern agro-biology
techniques.
</P>
<P>
A state-level lab on molecule ecology was also set up in the
institute focusing on the relationships between insects and plants,
sustained agricultural development, and control of pests and
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Say Genes Can Cause Nerve Center Malfunctions
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have found out that the activities of animal
's nerve center are controlled by certain genes.
</P>
<P>
A group of scientists from the No.4 Military Medical College in
this capital of northwest province of Shaanxi announced that they
have recorded nerve center malfunctions of a mouse after they
eliminated some genes from its genome.
</P>
<P>
China to Put DNA Sequence Databank on Internet
</P>
<P>
China has made a test run of putting its first DNA Sequence
Databank on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The databank, a state-financed information platform and
developed by the Shanghai Life Science Institute under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and the National Human Genome Research Center
of the Southern Institute of Genetics, will be officially opened
on the Internet by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Geneticists to Make Breakthroughs in Research
</P>
<P>
Chinese geneticists are confident that they will make another
two breakthroughs within one year as they quicken their pace of
genome research.
</P>
<P>
The first one is finishing their share of work on the
international Human Genome Project (HGP) by June 2001, two years
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The second one is to make China the first country in the world
to decode the super hybrid rice genome which is believed to ensure
China's leading position in hybrid rice research and production.
</P>
<P>
Book on Frontiers of Marine Science Published
</P>
<P>
A book on the frontiers of contemporary marine science was
published in July in Beijing. The book highlights 118 topics in
the frontiers of marine science.
</P>
<P>
The book covers marine-related physics, chemistry, geology,
biology and environment. And it is the product of the joint effort
of more than 100 Chinese oceanologists, with Su Jilan and Qin
Yunshan, both academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, as
its chief editors.
</P>
<P>
Int'l Forum on Oceanic Science Closes
</P>
<P>
A two-day international forum on oceanic science-technology and
economic development closed in the coastal city of Qingdao, in
China's Shandong Province on July 31.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 participants listened to reports delivered by
officials and experts from the Development Research Center under
the State Council, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the China
Association of Scientists and the State Oceanic Administration.
</P>
<P>
Technology Improving Crops' Photosynthesis Efficiency
</P>
<P>
A Chinese scientist has developed a kind of technology which
can greatly improve crops' photosynthesis efficiency, and helps
upgrade crops' quality and raise their output.
</P>
<P>
The Gene Phenotype Induction Technique was developed by Na
Zhongyuan, director of Yunnan Provincial Research Institute for
Ecological Agriculture, who spent a decade on related experiments.
</P>
<P>
Academicians Depicting Science Future
</P>
<P>
Fearsome cancers and leukemia stopped their gnawing bites on
people's lives. Ordinary people on the earth are enjoying their
interstellar travels aboard man-made flying objects.
</P>
<P>
These are not random talks at Arabian nights but some of the
forecasts of China's 60 academicians from the Chinese Academy of
Sciences and the Chinese Academy of Engineering on the scientific
and technological developments in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Titled " Academicians' Forecasts on the 21st Century", the book
has just come off the press.
</P>
<P>
School-Run Science Parks Develop Smoothly in China
</P>
<P>
Fifteen university-based science parks have been developing
smoothly in China over the past year.
</P>
<P>
This was learned at a national conference on university-run
science parks in Wuhan, the provincial capital of central Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Science and Technology and the
Ministry of Education attended the meeting. In their speeches,
officials stressed the importance of these science parks in
promoting the integration of science and technology, education and
the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporian Delegation Ends 4-day Visit to Cambodia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 45-member delegation led by Minister for Trade and Industry
George Yong-Boon Yeo arrived in Cambodia Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yong confirmed to Cambodia's Minister of Tourism Veng Sereyvudh
that Singapore's Silk Air will begin direct flights to the
Cambodian town of Siem Reap, home of the fabled 9th-12th century
Angkor temples on November 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore will be the third foreign airlines to have direct
flights to Siem Reap after the Bangkok Airways and Vietnam
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, a memorandum of understanding was signed
between the two sides on a joint project in Cambodia's capital at
about 5 million dollars for improvement of sewage system, water
dam and rubbish disposal.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegation has me with several Cambodian
leaders, including Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is the second largest investors in Cambodia after
Malaysia. 
</P>
