<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Consumers Gaining Mastery of PC, Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A global study released this
week has found rises in PC ownership and Internet use around the
world, but the divide between developed and developing countries
is only modestly closing.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of global consumers own a PC, up six percentage
points since 1998, while nearly one in five went on-line in the
past month, up seven points in the same period, according to the
study by Roper Starch Worldwide, a U.S. marketing research and
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on 30,000 face-to-face interviews with 1,000
consumers in each of 30 countries and regions, is projectable to 1.
39 billion people.
</P>
<P>
The biggest regional jump in PC ownership occurred in Asia, up
12 points from 1998. In second place, half of North Americans own
PCs, an eight-point gain over 1998. Third-place Latin America saw
a seven point rise.
</P>
<P>
Despite the gains in many parts of the world, Roper Starch
Worldwide said, the digital divide between developed and
developing countries is only modestly closing. The rate of
adopting information technology in more nascent economies is
faster than in developed countries, but it's from a base still
quite small, the research firm said.
</P>
<P>
Internet use is expanding at a pace similar to PC, according to
the study. North Americans are more likely than people in other
regions to have access to the Internet in the past 30 days, up 12
points since 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Chip Sales Rise To Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to data released by the Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA), chipmakers made a record sale of 16.6 U.S.
billion dollars in June, 48 percent from last June's 11.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It's also the fourth consecutive month in which the SIA
reported chip sales had reached a record high.
</P>
<P>
"June's numbers exceeded our expectations and affirm our
forecast for a strong 2000," George Scalise, SIA's president, said.
Earlier this year, the SIA revised upward its growth-rate forecast
to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Scalise said soaring demand for consumer products such as
wireless telephones, personal digital assistants and set-top boxes,
drove sales of flash memory, field programmable logic devices (
FPLDs), digital signal processors (DSPs), analog and
optoelectronics chips to the most substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
Flash sales were up 167 percent; FPLDs were up 106 percent; DSP
sales were 51 percent higher; analog sales rose 70 percent; and
optoelectronics chips sales came in 65 percent higher, the SIA
said.
</P>
<P>
Chips used in personal computers also rose substantially.
Dynamic random access memory (DRAM) sales were up 75 percent,
while microprocessor sales were 36 percent higher, the SIA
reported.
</P>
<P>
From a geographic standpoint, sales growth was stronger in Asia-
Pacific and Japanese markets, where they were up 52.8 percent and
50.8 percent, respectively. Sales in the Americas rose 42.7
percent. Europe's sales grew 48.1 percent, the SIA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
