<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Calls for Nuclear-Weapon-Free World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark has called for a nuclear-weapon-free world.
</P>
<P>
The call was made when she was addressing an Auckland gathering
Friday, which was held to mark the 55th anniversary since the use
of nuclear weapons on Japan's Nagasaki and Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, which was released by the Prime Minister's
Office here Friday, Helen Clark noted disarmament and arms control
are a major foreign policy priority for New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at ways of developing the concept of a southern
hemisphere free of nuclear weapons, as a further step towards a
nuclear-weapan-free world," she said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said disarmament and arms control are
processes that must constantly be pushed and in the processes, her
country can and should continue to play a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear, however, that New Zealand's pushing alone will
not be enough. Other countries must fulfill their commitments to
the elimination of weapons of mass destruction. There will need to
be more of the bold steps that New Zealand took in the mid-1980s.
We need public opinion world-wide mobilized again," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that the abolition of nuclear weapons will come
within reach when the tide of international opinion turns
decidedly against any role for nuclear weapons," the prime
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
