<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Rampant in Western U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 wildfires that
have scorched more than 700,000 acres of land are still burning in
11 U.S. western states, injuring firefighters, forcing hundreds of
evacuations, creating a haze that shrouded mountains and deserts,
according to local press reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Four firefighters suffered second-degree burns Wednesday as the
wind suddenly shifted while they were fighting against one of
several big blazes that have blackened some 83,000 acres of
California timber and bushes. Two of them were hospitalized and
remained in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, California firefighters made big gains against a
giant fire burning atop the southern Sierra Nevada, and
California's biggest blaze, which had burned 72,200 acres in
Sequoia National Forest on the east side of the Southern Sierra,
was 40 percent contained.
</P>
<P>
August is traditionally the worst month for wildfires which are
a natural part of the ecosystems of the western United States. The
current combination in the area of high temperatures, low humidity
and lightning unaccompanied by rain create perfect conditions for
them.
</P>
<P>
Dry lightning during the past two days sparked hundreds of new
fires, including 17 major blazes in California, Utah, Montana and
Nevada. Fires are also raging in Colorado, Arizona, Idaho, New
Mexico, Texas, Washington and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
Federal officials said this year's fire season could be the
worst in 30 years. They said the cost incurred in suppressing the
fires could exceed one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The federal government is spending 15 million dollars a day to
support the 20,000 civilian and military firefighters from 46
states and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The Marines and the Army are providing 1,200 troops for fire
duty, and nearly 500 National Guard and Reserve troops are
involved at the request of various state governors.
</P>
<P>
In Montana, two new fires started on Wednesday evening and
burned 900 acres in the southwestern part of the state. Eleven
other blazes have burned at least 131,100 acres. Throughout the
state, residents have been evacuated from more than 300 homes.
</P>
<P>
A fire sparked by lightning burned 4,000 acres and forced
evacuations in southwest Reno, Nevada. But firefighters said
Wednesday that improving weather overnight let them contain 65
percent of the blaze.
</P>
<P>
Utah firefighters are battling against nearly 55,000 acres of
wildfires, including six that have consumed more than 48,000 acres
in the Fishlake National Forest, as they await reinforcements from
the state National Guard. Crews have contained about 30 percent of
the Fishlake inferno.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck toured the Idaho and
Montana fire lines to review the safety of fire crews and pledged
that they will be given adequate resources.
</P>
<P>
Canadian firefighters are on the lines, and resources have been
stretched so thin that federal officials were considering bringing
in crews from Mexico and technical experts from Australia.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 62,000 wildfires have been reported across the nation
this year, scorching more than 3.7 million acres, the highest
total since at least the mid-1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Southwest Airlines Fires Two Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Southwest Airlines has
fired the pilot and the co-pilot of a Boeing 737 that crashed
through a fence in March on landing in Burbank, California, in the
carrier's worst accident, the airline said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A Southwest Airlines spokesman, Ed Stuart, declined to name the
pilot and the co-pilot, or to specify on what grounds they were
dismissed, saying the causes of the accident were part of an
ongoing investigation by the U.S. National Transportation Safety
Board (NTSB).
</P>
<P>
Their contracts "were terminated as a result of what we
uncovered in our investigation," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal came after the company completed an internal
investigation of the March 5 crash of Flight 1455, the first major
accident in the low-fare carrier's 29-year history.
</P>
<P>
The flight from Las Vegas, carrying 142 passengers and crew,
overshot the runway at Burbank Airport, ran through a chain link
fence and across a six-lane road before stopping just short of the
fuel pumps of a gas station.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen people were hurt, including the pilots, but no one was
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The Southwest Airlines Pilots Association filed a grievance
after the sacking, which were effective on July 17, a spokeswoman
for the association said.
</P>
<P>
Investigators said the plane made its final descent into
Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena Airport at such a steep angle that a
cockpit warning system went off, and it was going 208 mph (333
kilometers per hour) at touchdown when it should have been going
around 161 mph (258 kilometers per hour).
</P>
<P>
Safety board officials said the captain, a 12-year Southwest
Airlines veteran with 18,000 flight hours, was at the plane's
control during the landing. The co-pilot was hired by the company
in 1996 and had been flying for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Southwest Airlines, the seventh largest air carrier of the
United States, has not had a fatality in its 30-year history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population of Chinese Sturgeons Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The population of the Chinese
sturgeon, one of the oldest vertebrates in the world considered to
be at risk of extinction, has grown, thanks to the successful
artificial breeding technology.
</P>
<P>
More than 250,000 human-bred sturgeon samplings have been
released to the major rivers in south China including the Yangtze
and Pearl rivers over the past two years. They were born in a
dozen breeding farms for Chinese sturgeons in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the giant panda, the endangered fish species has a
fairly high reproductive ability, according to Wei Qiwei, a
research fellow with the China Association of Fishery Sciences. A
mature sturgeon can spawn 630,000 eggs.
</P>
<P>
China has developed an advanced artificial breeding technology
of the Chinese sturgeon, which can increase the eggs' incubation
rate to 95 percent, from one percent in natural condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0208 </DOCNO>
