<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Receives 19.11 Bln U.S. Dollars of Remittances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has earned over 19.11
billion U.S. dollars of remittances from expatriates serving
abroad till June 2000, according to the statistics of the Bureau
of Manpower, Employment and Training released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
More than 3 million people have managed their livelihoods
abroad, mainly in the Middle East countries, since beginning of
foreign employment for Bangladeshi citizens in 1976, the
statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Of the Bangladeshi people doing jobs in different countries in
the world, more than 0.11 million are professional workers, 0.88
million are skilled workers, 0.63 million are semi-skilled workers
and 1.27 million people are unskilled workers.
</P>
<P>
The country earned the highest amount of remittance from non-
resident Bangladeshi people in 1999, amounting to 1.9 billion
dollars. More than 0.26 million people were expatriated to
different countries around the globe that year.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the single largest country where the maximum
number of Bangladeshi people work. More than 1.35 million people
representing 45.07 percent of the total expatriates have found
jobs in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is the second largest country employing Bangladeshis
whose number stood over 0.38 million representing 12.81 percent of
the total number of expatriates.
</P>
<P>
United Arab Emirates and Kuwait are in third and fourth
positions with over 0.34 million and 0.30 million people
respectively working there.
</P>
<P>
Besides, significant numbers of Bangladeshis went to Qatar,
Iraq, Libya, Bahrain, Oman, South Korea, Singapore and Brunei in
search of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many Bangladeshis are working in the United States, Briton,
Italy, Canada and some other European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt to Assess Status of Dengue Prevalence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is going
for a scientific study to assess the current status of dengue
prevalence and its type in Dhaka city, The Daily Star reported
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a high-level meeting at the Health
Ministry, which was also attended by representatives from Local
Government Ministry, Dhaka City Corporation and non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The month-long study titled Integrated Approach of Prevention
and Control of Dengue in Bangladesh, began Thursday at the Dhaka
Shishu Hospital where blood samples of dengue patients are being
collected and stored.
</P>
<P>
The government is funding the study conducted by the Institute
of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research (IEDCR) which covers
10 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Two more people died of dengue hemorrhagic fever Thursday,
bringing the total number of deaths from the dreaded disease to 17
in the city, according to hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
"We've experienced dengue fever since 1964, but it was largely
classic dengue. What really worries us is the high incidence of
dengue hemorrhagic fever, which is caused by cross infection of
two distinct types of viruses," said Dr. Alamgir, a senior
virologist at the IEDCR.
</P>
<P>
There is substantive evidence that serial infection by
different dengue viruses may increase the risk of being affected
by more serious diseases such as dengue hemorrhagic fever, he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
