<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Federal Agencies To Cut Power Use In California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton
Thursday ordered federal agencies in California to cut their power
use by an estimated five percent to ease a crunch in the state's
electricity supplies because of near-record demand inspired by
broiling heat.
</P>
<P>
"Currently the supply of electrical power is tight in
California due to record demand for electricity. The state faces
rolling blackouts in some areas. These conditions put both
customers and businesses at risk," Clinton said in the order to
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
He also said federal agencies that produce or market
electricity must do what they could to increase power availability
in California.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, California Gov. Gray Davis ordered a probe into
possible market manipulation. Davis also vowed to seek to speed up
the approval process for desperately needed new power plants.
</P>
<P>
California's power emergency escalated Thursday afternoon as
scorching heat held demand near record level and some industrial
and commercial customers lost electricity for the fourth
consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
The California Independent System Operator (ISO), which manages
most of California's power grid, said peak demand for electricity
Thursday afternoon was expected to reach 45,723 megawatts (MW),
close to the record 45,877 MW set on July 12, 1999.
</P>
<P>
California's power problems are rooted partly in surging demand
linked to strong economic growth in the western United States.
</P>
<P>
The state is the home of Silicon Valley, the center of the
nation's booming high-technology industry. Economists estimate
that power outages would cost companies in that region at least 75
million dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
Instead of building more power plants, some experts point out
that intense heat occurs typically about 15 days a year and
building power plants just for those occasions might be a very
expensive approach.
</P>
<P>
They urge people to reduce power consumption by closing drapes
or blinds to keep out sunlight, refrain from opening refrigerators,
cook and do laundry during off-peak hours and use fans instead of
air conditioners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
