<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Endemic Mangroves Face Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Rizophora, a mangrove species
endemic to Sri Lanka, is on the verge of extinction, according to
a latest report by the United Nations Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The report said Rizophora on the southwestern coat of Sri Lanka
has almost disappeared due to the clearance of mangrove areas to
make ponds to raise fish and prawns.
</P>
<P>
"Mangrove forests have been cut for fodder, timber, firewood,
production of charcoal, cultivation and land reclamation. These
have attributed to their alarming reduction," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that about a million hectares of mangrove
forests have been converted to aquaculture ponds all over the
world and the genus Rizophora is becoming rare on the southwestern
coast of Sri Lanka and the eastern coast of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Mangroves cover nearly 24 million hectares all over the world,
of which a third occurs in the Asia-Pacific region. But widespread
clearance has led to mass destruction of this valuable flora.
</P>
<P>
The report cited mangrove areas as a particularly important
ecosystem, providing vital feeding and nursery grounds for prawns
and fish while protecting the coastal areas from erosion. They act
as a buffer against tidal current, flood and storm, it said.
</P>
<P>
It warned that since mangroves forms an indispensable link in
the aquatic ecosystem, it is extremely important to protect the
mangrove cover and that neglect to do so could seriously break
down the functions of this vital link. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drunk Driving Purge Cuts Accident Toll in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Road accidents in Bangkok have
fallen by 43 percent after a year-long police campaign against
drunk driving, and the number of damaged wire poles has dropped
accordingly, the Bangkok Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thai traffic police chief Adul Saengsingkaew was quoted as
saying that there were 21,411 road accidents reported in the
capital from June 1999 to May this year, a 43.68 percent drop from
the same period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The death toll fell to 397 from 515 and damage assessment to
143 million baht (3.57 million U.S. dollars) from 238 million baht
(5.95 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The improved road safety was also reflected by the Metropolitan
Electricity Authority's record of accidents involving wire poles,
which shrank to 944 from 1,319.
</P>
<P>
Thai traffic police began booking drunk motorists on July 16,
1999. As of July 28 this year, 2,090 drivers were found to have
alcohol in their blood. They were sentenced to two months
imprisonment, fined 4,000 baht each (100 dollars) and their
driving licenses were suspended for two years.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they must report regularly to probation officers
for a year and spend 12 hours on social service such as cleaning
public places and telling stories in schools for the blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
