<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Thirds of Austrians Against Referendum on EU Sanction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A new poll result showed that
about 67 percent Austrians opposed holding a referendum to force
the other 14 EU states to lift political sanctions against the
country, the Austria Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Only 25 percent people inquired welcomed the referendum
scheduled for this autumn, while more than 60 percent considered
the plan as "an absolute nonsense".
</P>
<P>
The referendum plan was approved by Chancellor Wolfgang
Schuessel and far-rightist Joerg Haider in early July, after other
EU governments froze political contacts with Austria because of
Haider's Freedom Party's entry into the government in February.
</P>
<P>
Haider, governor of Carinthia and a figure Austria's EU
partners view as racist and unfit for government, has resigned as
the leader of the party but remains as a political guru.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that 74 percent of Austrians wanted their
country to stay in the EU, although 49 percent of Austrians were
angered by the EU's sanctions. Austrians' attitude toward the EU's
eastern enlargement seems even more positive.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous employee working for the poll explained the reason
of the contradictions, saying that "although Austrians like to
grumble, they are true realistic opportunists".
</P>
<P>
Last year, trade volumes with central and east European
countries accounted for 9.7 percent and 15 percent of Austria's
total foreign trade, respectively. Austria has thus gained
thousands of job opportunities and registered a trade surplus of
31.3 billion Schilling (22.8 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, W.Bank Urge Bosnian Serbs to Take Swift Action to Improve Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the World Bank Thursday urged the Bosnian Serb
authorities to take swift action to improve the republic's
flagging economy, otherwise future economic assistance from
international financial institutions could be affected.
</P>
<P>
Bruno De Sacen, IMF representative in Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Thursday said in Banja Luka that the budget deficit of the Serbs'
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegoniva may have reached up to about 200
million German marks (90 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
To solve the imbalance, the Serb government must take actions
against peculation and graft and also fight against rampant
smuggling, Bruno advised.
</P>
<P>
The smuggling in cigarettes alone last year resulted in 200
million German marks (90 million dollars) worth of losses for the
government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a World Bank official based in Bosnia-Herzegovina
also urged the Bosnian Serb government to take measures to ensure
workers and pensioners receive their pay properly and on schedule.
</P>
<P>
The two financial organizations warned that if the government
failed to improve its economic conditions, their future economic
assistance and loans to the republic would be in doubt. 
</P>
