<HEADLINE> China News Digest: West on the Move (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirty doctors from seven Chinese prestigious universities
including Beijing and Qinghua universities have been making study
tours in Tibet since the beginning of July to explore ways for the
development of this southwest China autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Tibet, they held discussions with local
government officials and representatives from enterprises on
topics involving scientific and technological development and
education, and held training courses for local industrial and
mineral enterprises, government organs and schools.
</P>
<P>
Many of them expressed the intention to work in Tibet, where
they said that they can make full use of local rich natural,
tourism and cultural resources in their research work.
</P>
<P>
China has in the past weeks sent 2,000 doctors to make study
tours in Xinjiang, Tibet and other areas in the country's vast
western region.
</P>
<P>
World Bank Loans Supporting Western China Development
</P>
<P>
The World Bank (WB) will adopt more preferential policies to
support China in developing its vast western region, a World Bank
official said recently after an study tour of Gansu province in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
China's development of its western region will provide more
opportunities for cooperation between the Chinese government and
the World Bank, the official added.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, Gansu has already implemented 21 WB-
financed projects which use loans totaling 653 million U.S.
dollars. And nine of the projects have been completed.
</P>
<P>
These projects covering Gansu's 14 prefectures and cities
involve agriculture, water control, forestry, education, public
health, transportation and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, World Bank will focus on supporting
the construction of water supply, environment protection, and
pollution-control projects in western China in the future.
</P>
<P>
 Xinjiang Reports Fast Economic Growth
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region reported a
favorable turn in economic growth in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the region's industrial production became
profitable with net earnings of 2.1 billion yuan for the first
time in the past five years. The sales output ratio of industrial
products in Xinjiang reached 99.1 percent, ranking first in China.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises under all kinds of ownership perform well. The
output value of new products rose 76 percent. The losses of the
textile industry dropped by a big margin. The investment in fixed
assets increased by 14.6 percent, with the state sector accounting
for 80 percent of the total fixed-asset investment.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose more than 50 percent in the first five months.
Cotton made up 41 percent of the total exports. The fiscal revenue
of Xinjiang totaled 6.7 billion yuan in the first six months, up
by about 20 percent over last year's same period.
</P>
</TEXT>
