<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karst Cave Found North of Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A karst cave formed 1.4
billion years ago was recently discovered in Xinglong County,
northeast of the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling of the cave, located in Wuling Mountain in Xinglong,
is only 3.7 meters away from the mountain's peak.
</P>
<P>
The cave consists of three sections, 500, 200 and 300 meters
long respectively, at different elevations. It is 28 meters at the
highest place and 30 meters at the widest.
</P>
<P>
The cave was once the recluse place for Master Gong Chang, the
founder of a Buddhist branch, in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). He
wrote his scriptures there, local relics protection officials said.
There are still some josses and writing tables in the cave.
</P>
<P>
Over 15,000 people from at home and abroad have visited the
cave since it was found.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
