<HEADLINE> Progress Achieved in West China's Water Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Breakthroughs have been recorded
in explorations for water in China's arid western regions, which
will be able to fetch from underground one billion more cubic
meters of water each year.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 sites of water and sections with rich underground
water have been located by the country's water explorers in the
regions, according to today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The huge amount of the newly explored underground water is
estimated to be that contained in some 10 large-scale reservoirs.
It will help to alleviate the acute water shortage problems in the
under-developed western regions.
</P>
<P>
The breakthroughs were partly attributed to the adoption of new
exploration technologies, such as remote sensing and nuclear
magnetic resonance.  
</P>
