<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City Dwellers Enjoy More Spare Time: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- City dwellers in China are
enjoying more spare time now thanks to decreased time spent on
work and housework, the Beijing-based Guangming Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 10 years, the average spare time for the urban
Chinese has increased by 64 minutes, while the time spent on
routine work has shrinked by 114 minutes, according to an academic
survey carried out by a professor from the People's University of
China.
</P>
<P>
Spare time almost made up one third of the life of an ordinary
Chinese, while the work time only accounts for a mere 10 percent,
the survey found.
</P>
<P>
However, half of the spare time of the city dwellers was spent
before the TV sets. The time spent on TV watching soared to three
hours and 38 minutes, doubling that of ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
How to properly arrange one's spare time is a challenge for not
only the individuals but also the nation as a whole, Guangming
noted.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the time the average Japanese and
Americans spent on watching TV were just one hour and 37 minutes,
and two hours and 14 minutes, respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to those countries, our way of dealing with spare
time seems too monotonous," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, that also means that the prospects for China to
develop industries of recreation and traveling are fairly bright,
the paper added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
