<HEADLINE> Thailand develops Satellite for Internet Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Thai telecommunication
conglomerate is developing a new satellite to be specially used
for facilitating internet users in Thailand and other countries in
Asia and the Pacific, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, developed by Shin Satellite Corporation and
designed by Thai architects, would have up to 1,000 signal
channels, and facilitate the use of internet more smoothly and
faster, compared to telephone lines, with reasonable costs, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The 14 billion baht (about 35 million U.S. dollars satellite
with higher efficiency and capacity could be on services by 2002
or 2003, it said.
</P>
<P>
Internet users in Thailand and other countries in Asia and the
Pacific, namely China and India, would benefit from the new Thai
satellite, it stated.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that 500 million people in China, 100 million in
India, and 600,000 in Thailand will apply for the new service, it
added. 
</P>
