<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Reserve to Be Established at Source of Pearl R. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
plans to establish a nature reserve at the source of the Pearl
River, the third longest in China, to protect the ecological
environment at its headwaters.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory work for the 200,000-ha swamp nature reserve is
under way, officials in the Forestry Department of Yunnan Province
said.
</P>
<P>
The 2210-km Pearl River originates from Maxiong Mountain in
Qujing City of Yunnan and flows across six administrative regions
including Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Qujing City established a county-level nature reserve in 1998,
with an investment of 50 million yuan (six million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The city's forest coverage rate is 27 percent at present, and
its soil erosion areas account for 49 percent of the total Pearl
River Valleys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
