<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Heat Islands Simmering Big Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua)-- " Urban heat islands" are
simmering big cities and to be blamed for the skyrocketing
temperatures, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the traditional evils of vehicle emissions and
heat from kitchen ranges, the scorching days in big cities can be
attributed to the reflections from glass-fronted buildings.
</P>
<P>
"Glass fronts on high buildings contribute greatly to the hot
weather because they reflect sunlight and create both light and
heat pollution," said Li Yanfu, an engineer with the Beijing
Meteorological Observatory.
</P>
<P>
A survey was done at 2:30 pm on July 25 in a popular shopping
area in Beijing, where many buildings with glass fronts stand side
by side.
</P>
<P>
Researchers found that temperature in the reflection area was
38 C while the unreflected area was 37.4 C, and in the nearby
shade of trees, it was only 35.8 C.
</P>
<P>
With no regulations to curb the construction of buildings with
glass fronts, China has seen increasing number of complaints about
light and heat pollution caused by the shining buildings in recent
years, sources from environmental protection departments said.
</P>
<P>
To ease the pressure on environment, the most important thing
is to plant more trees and grass in downtown areas to replace high
buildings, according to Lian Kaiming, a professor from the Qinghua
University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver Iodide Used to Improve Rainfall Outside of Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have succeeded in
increasing rainfalls in Beijing's Miyun County simply by burning
silver iodide in a gas stove at the top of a mountain.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Huanyong, a senior engineer with the county's
meteorological bureau and his colleagues climbed to a mountain top,
800 meters above the sea level in Miyun County Wednesday morning
and burned silver iodide for more than four hours till it began to
rain in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The method has worked well and we got 20 mm of precipitation
north of the Miyun Reservoir and 64 mm of precipitation in the
northeast part of the county," said Zhao.
</P>
<P>
He explained that when the smog produced by the boiled silver
iodide enter the cloud, it will have chemical reaction with vapor
in the cloud and help increase the precipitation.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Beijing has used such a method to
increase rain, said Zhang Qiang. He said if the method continues
to prove successful, it will be widely used in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, another group of experts failed to use
airplanes to increase rainfall in Changping County because of
thunder and lighting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
