<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Navy Ends High Sea Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian navy ended a 17-day
standoff on the high seas off Newfoundland Thursday by boarding
and escorting the GTS Katie cargo ship toward the Gulf of St.
Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
"The Canadian navy began boarding the Katie on order of the
government of Canada," and then two navy ships were escorting the
ship to the Canadian coast, military spokesman Daryl Morrell said
in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
The action followed Wednesday's ultimatum by the Canadian
government that the owner of the ship, the U.S.-based Third Ocean
Marine Navigation, accept an offer of 90,000 Canadian dollars (60,
800 U.S. dollars) as a first step to end the dispute that delayed
the docking of Canadian military equipment in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Third Ocean rejected the offer, insisting on an initial
agreement of payment of 190,000 Canadian dollars (128,350 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company also claims that the Montreal-based Andromeda
Navigation owes it 294,000 Canadian dollars (198,600 dollars) for
transporting about 580 army vehicles and 390 sea containers with
munitions from Kosovo to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Peter Margan of the Third Ocean said late Thursday that the
National Defense Department of Canada is now brokering the
negotiations between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
"There are negotiations going on, but there's no update just
yet," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Katie has been circling in international waters off the
coast of Newfoundland since mid-July, when it was due in Montreal
with a treasure-trove of Canadian military equipment worth 223
million Canadian dollars (151 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
