<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Type Specimen Discovered in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A group of scientists from China,
Australia, Britain and Germany have recently discovered a number
of type specimen that had remained unknown for more than a century
in Shanghai Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
These specimen are all mammal bones, including a boar skull, a
roe deer skull and a bear skull.
</P>
<P>
A species has only one type specimen, which acts as the object
of reference in species classification.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have confirmed the newly discovered type
specimen were made by a French scholar surnamed Heude, who
discovered these mammal species in India, Vietnam, Laos, and
Cambodia in mid-1900s.
</P>
<P>
These type specimen, along with another 20,000 specimen of
other animals, had been kept in the Heude Museum, predecessor of
Shanghai Museum of Natural History, one of China's largest museums.
</P>
<P>
They had not come to light until three scientists from Britain,
Germany and Australia read about the type specimen in a natural
history book by Heude in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The scientists then joined their Chinese counterparts and
sorted out these rare specimen from a collection of some 240,000
items in Shanghai Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
"These specimen are priceless because man has discovered nearly
all mammal species on earth and it's almost impossible to obtain a
new mammal type specimen, " said Zhang Nianshi, an expert on
mammal specimen with the museum.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Museum of Natural History now boasts more than 900
type specimen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Philosopher to Give Lecture at Confucian Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese philosopher Tang Yijie
will step to a rostrum that has been fallen into disuse for
thousands of years at the Temple of Confucius (B.C.551-B.C.479) in
Qufu of east China's Shandong Province this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tang, also vice chairman of China Society of Confucius, will
discuss global issues ranging from rational development of the
nature, peaceful sharing of resources, to rescuing the mankind
from spiritual crisis in his lecture entitled "Thoughts in Pursuit
of Global Ethics".
</P>
<P>
Tang will take the style of Confucius, who was said to lecture
3,000 disciples while being seated at the rostrum inside the
Temple of Confucius, which was put onto the UNESCO World Heritage
List in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Tang's lecture giving will be televised by Hunan Provincial
Satellite Television Station, sources from the TV service said.
The event is part of the program "2000 Forum" launched by the
station.
</P>
<P>
Previously, a number of other Chinese specialists or overseas
scholars of Chinese origin, including Charles Zhang, President of
Sohu. Com, a Chinese website portal, and Chinese economist Fan
Gang were also invited to give lectures at renowned Yuelu Academy
based in Changsha, capital of Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Confucius was a great thinker, philosopher and educator who
lived in the late Spring and Autumn Period (B.C.770-B.C. 476). He
set up a sort of private school -- the earliest in Chinese history.
He taught all who came to learn from him, bringing education to
the ordinary people and breaking the monopoly of education by the
nobility.  He also founded Confucianism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
