<HEADLINE> Literature Archives Launches Regular Lectures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Modern Chinese Literature
Archives recently launched literary lectures on Sundays given by
well-known writers.
</P>
<P>
On five Sundays from July 30 to August 27, Shu Yi, Wu Fuhui,
Lan Dizhi, Wang Furen and Chen Pingyuan were scheduled to deliver
speeches featuring topics such as treasures of the literature
archives, Chinese masterpieces and their authors, and
consciousness analysis on writing, Wenhui Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Common readers could freely participate in the lectures, the
Shanghai-based newspaper said. In the future, organized readers
could also choose lecturers for specific topics they have interest
in.
</P>
<P>
At the first occasion of its kind on July 30, the lecture hall
with hundreds of seats was crammed by audience.
</P>
<P>
The archives, which is located in northern Beijing and opened
to the public in May, is now China's largest modern literature
research center and library where all literary works and reviews
published since 1911 are stored.
</P>
<P>
The facility, serving as a literature museum, library, archives
and center for literature research and exchange, holds some 300,
000 books. 
</P>
</TEXT>
