<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is expected to
give top priority to forming a new coalition with Meretz and Shas
parties, The Jerusalem Post newspaper quoted a source of the ruling
One Israel as reporting on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Barak believes he can overcome the differences between Meretz
and Shas that led to the June coalition crisis which resulted in
the resignation of three Meretz cabinet ministers, including
Education Minister Yossi Sarid, the source added. (Israel-Barak-
Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will arrive in Turkey
on Saturday to update Turkish leaders on the latest developments of
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to meet with Turkish President Ahmet Necdet
Sezer, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
during his brief visit, Anatolia News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will brief Turkish leaders on his steadfast stance on
declaring an independent Palestinian state on September 13 no
matter whether there is a peace agreement with Israel or not.
(Turkey-Arafat-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The United Nations Friday expressed regret at the
cancellation of exchange of visits between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. heard late Thursday afternoon from the Turkish
Cypriots that they will not agree to the Greek Cypriot request to
have the check point at Strovilia removed and the measures against
UNFICYP (U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus) lifted," spokeswoman
for the U.N. Sarah Russell said. (Cyprus-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammed Mahdi Saleh and his
party arrived here Friday afternoon to attend the meeting of the
Syrian-Iraqi Joint Ministerial Committee, the first over the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Saleh told reporters that he would discuss
with Syrian leaders ways of enhancing economic, trade and
scientific cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also discuss the resumption of technical and
cultural ties and cooperation in the field of land and marine
transport, including exploitation of the Syrian Latakia seaport as
a transit point for Iraqi imports. (Syria-Iraq-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Baku-Ceyhan pipeline, aimed at transferring
Caspian oil to western markets via Turkey, is "unfeasible" and
unlikely to be realized in the near future, Iranian Deputy Oil
Minister Muhammad Nejad has said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Turkish Daily News on Wednesday, Nejad said
that Tehran considered the Baku-Ceyhan project to be "uneconomical"
and difficult to be constructed due to its route. (Turkey-Iran-
Pipeline) 
</P>
</TEXT>
