<HEADLINE> Nigerian AIDS Patients Take Government to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 142 Nigerian HIV/AIDS
sufferers have taken their government to court over its recent ban
on a locally-produced HIV/AIDS vaccine developed by an Abuja-based
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS patients, filing a law suit on Friday to the
federal high court in Abuja, claimed that the ban equals to death
sentence for them and is a violation of their rights under the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Jeremiah Abalaka, inventor of the vaccine, is the most well
known among the numerous Nigerian medical doctors, chemists and
spiritualists, who have claimed that they have found a cure for
the deadly pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Despite that quite a number of people believe in the
effectiveness of the vaccine, an investigative panel by the
Nigerian Academy of Science dismissed it after carrying out
relevant medical experiments.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which has about 3 million people living with HIV/AIDS,
is among the top rank in the African continent in term of the size
of HIV/AIDS population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
