<HEADLINE> UNAMSIL Asks for More Troops in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Missions in
Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) has asked for more troops as quickly as
possible to strengthen the peacekeeping missions in the war-torn
west African country, a report reaching here on Friday said.
</P>
<P>
Vijay Jetley, commander of the U.N. peacekeeping forces in
Sierra Leone, was quoted as saying on Thursday that the situation
there is currently under UNAMSIL's control, but it is still tense.
</P>
<P>
He said he needs "many more" troops to bolster defenses against
heavily-armed rebels of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) and
push forward the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 13,000 personnel in Sierra Leone, UNAMSIL is
already the biggest peacekeeping operation in the world ever
launched by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Following the abduction of about 500 U.N. peacekeepers by the
RUF in May this year, the United Nations Security Council resolved
to enlarge the force of UNAMSIL to 16,500 to help the Sierra Leone
government regain territory still controlled by the RUF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
