<HEADLINE> U.N. to Start Deploying Peacekeepers Throughout Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- For the first time since
it was established 22 years ago, the United Nations Interim Force
in Lebanon (UNIFIL) is now able to implement Security Council
Resolution 425 by deploying throughout southern Lebanon, a U.N.
spokesman said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. deputy Spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said the green
light for expanded deployment of the Force was given by Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud to U.N. Force Commander Major General Seth
Kofi Obeng this morning.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeepers will start the final phase of their
deployment along the Lebanese-Israeli border on Saturday, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a historical moment for UNIFIL that after nearly 22
years it is able to implement United Nations Security Council
Resolution 425 of 1978," Silva said.
</P>
<P>
"The troops, supported by the Force Mobile Reserve, will move
to more than 20 new positions in villages and along the Blue Line,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeepers should have been deployed in southern
Lebanon 10 days ago. The deployment did not began until last
Friday due to the new Israeli violations of its border with
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced the complete withdrawal of its troops from
southern Lebanon on May 24 which ended its 22-year-long occupation
of the area.
</P>
<P>
The Blue Line was drawn by the United Nations to verify Israel
's complete withdrawal of troops from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
According the United Nations, the expanded deployment will
involve about 800 troops, with 35-40 peacekeepers occupying each
position. Currently, about 150 troops are deployed at six
positions along the Blue Line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
