<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. State Department Needs 300 Mln Dlrs for Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
would have 300 million dollars over three years to improve its
security at the accident-prone buildings that runs U.S. diplomacy,
U.S. officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The money is to be used to implement recommendations presented
to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright by an expert team in May,
including a proposal to increase by 150 percent the number of
security officers employed by the department.
</P>
<P>
Under one of the 43 recommendations contained in the report,
900 new security positions -- including uniformed agents, couriers,
security engineers and technicians -- would be created to
supplement the existing 400-500 uniformed guards who patrol the
building and grounds now, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Other suggestions include creating guard posts outside the
State Department's headquarters for identification checks and bag
searches and instituting thorough checks of cars that park in the
building's underground garage.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the spending plan has not passed through all
State Department procedures and has not gone to Congress, which
would have to approve the spending.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has been tightening security gradually for
more than a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
