<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges Rwanda, Others to Pull Out of D.R. Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- France Friday urged Rwanda and
other countries involved in the war in the Democratic Republic of
Congo to pull their troops out of the country, after Uganda
announced that it is pulling out its troops.
</P>
<P>
"France takes note of the announcement on the pullout of the
Ugandan battalion, which the observers of the Mission of the
United Nations are yet to confirm. France calls on Rwanda, then
the other countries militarily present in the Democratic Republic
of Congo to make the same gesture in their turn," said French
Foreign Ministry assistant spokesman Bernard Valero.
</P>
<P>
In its Resolution 1304, the United Nations Security Council
calls on all the foreign countries involved in the war in Congo to
pull out their troops and foresees the deployment of a
peacekeeping force there.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda support the two rival rebel groups while
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia support the government forces of
President Laurent-Desire Kabila since a civil war broke out in
October 1998.
</P>
<P>
France also wishes that Kabila will support and guarantee the
deployment of a 5,500-man United Nations peacekeeping force in his
country, including the capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese rebels, supported by Ugandan and Rwandan troops,
now control the northern and eastern parts of the country, while
Kabila's forces and their allies control the western and southern
parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
