<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Extends Mandate of U.N. Force in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday voted unanimously to extend the mandate of the U.N. Mission
in Sierra Leone, called the UNAMSIL, until September 8, while U.N.
officials prepare recommendations to beef up the peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
Although UNAMSIL Commander Indian Major General Vijay Jetley
told reporters Thursday he had asked the Security Council for "
many more troops" to increase from the current authorized strength
of 13,000 troops, the council resolution did not mention the
increase.
</P>
<P>
The resolution asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
provide recommendations as soon as possible for restructuring and
beefing up the force.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also gives the UNAMSIL a tougher mandate to
deal with rebels violating a peace accord signed by the rebels and
government in Lome, capital of Togo, in July last year. The
UNAMSIL was sent into the war-torn country to monitor the peace
accord, which was intended to end the eight-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said attacks on the UNAMSIL by the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) had "revealed serious inherent
weaknesses in the mission's structure, command and control and
resources."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force is also due to "deter, and where necessary,
decisively counter the threat of RUF attack by responding robustly
to any hostile actions" or threat of imminent use of force, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The RUF, led by Foday Sankoh, violated the peace accord by
taking more than 500 U.N. soldiers hostage and surrounding 223
others for more than two months in the eastern part of the West
African country. Sankoh is currently in the government custody in
Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the "widespread and serious
violations" of the Lome agreement by the RUF "constitute a
breakdown of the prior generally permissive environment based on
the agreement" and predicted on the cooperation of the parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Until security conditions allow progress toward the peaceful
resolution of the conflict, "there will continue to be a threat to
UNAMSIL and the security of the state of Sierra Leone," the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said that it intended to strengthen the
UNAMSIL's capability, resources and mandate and set out a number
of priority tasks. These include maintaining the security of the
Lungi and Freetown peninsulas, where the main airport and capital
are located, as well as their major approach routes.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to recommend adding several battalions,
raising the force strength to around 16,500 troops, although in a
recent report he said increasing the UNAMSIL's strength would
depend on the willingness of U.N. members to provide the necessary
well-trained, well-equipped soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
