<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Online Travel Revenues Make Up Third of All Online Sales in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Growth in consumer-directed
online travel-related sales is accelerating, presently makes up 33.
5 percent of all online consumer revenues in the United States,
according to a new report released this week.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the travel market unseated the computer hardware and
software category as the leader in total online revenue, said the
report from Internet statistics monitor eMarketer. The market will
take off from 6 billion U.S. dollars in 1999 to 12.4 billion
dollars by the end of 2000, eventually touching down at 25.2
billion dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Factors contributing to the growth include the growing
population of people buying online, the rise in individual
spending on the Internet, travel planning on the Internet enabling
the consumer to compare costs and services, the convenience
services such as electronic tickets and online reservations, and
the growing number of American travelers.
</P>
<P>
There is a large untapped market potential for online travel-
related services in Europe, Asia and Latin America, the report
said. The worldwide business-to-consumer sector of e-commerce will
rise from 30.1 billion dollars in 1999, accounting for 29 percent
of total e-commerce globally, to 187.6 billion dollars in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
