<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Agree to Stronger Sanctions Against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
have agreed to make joint efforts in imposing additional U.S.
Security Council sanctions against Taliban-led Afghanistan for
refusing to hand over suspected terrorist Osama Bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Philip Reeker said Friday that the
agreement was reached when a bilateral working group on
Afghanistan met here earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Reeker said the two sides called for full implementation of a U.
N. resolution approved last November under which all member states
are required to freeze the overseas assets of Afghanistan and ban
flights owned, leased or operated by the Taliban from taking off
or landing.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that a multifaceted approach, including
diplomatic, law enforcement and other legal means, is required to
counter the "threat of international terrorism from Afghanistan
and to create conditions for the establishment of a broad-based
government in the country," Reek added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Washington and Moscow also condemned "Taliban's
promotion of the illicit production and trafficking of drugs in
territory under their control and the use of drug profits to
support terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Washington has accused Bin Laden of being responsible for the
August 1998 bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
