<DOCNO> XIE20000804.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Airlines Suffers Loss Due to Fuel Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Airlines (EAL) has
incurred loss in its commercial operations of this fiscal year
that ended in early July, local Monitor newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bisrat Negatu, chief executive officer of the EAL, was quoted
as saying that within one year the fuel budget of his company has
unexpectedly escalated by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared to that of 1997/98 fiscal year, the budget has shown
an increase of over 300 million birr (about 37.3 million U.S.
dollars), Bisrat said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures for the last fiscal year reveal that EAL's
revenue increased by only 19.5 percent while its cost rose by 23.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The commercial loss of the EAL was also attributed to the two-
year-old Ethio-Eritrean border war, during which the decrease in
the number of passengers and volume of cargo has been significant,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
During its latest round of border conflict with Eritrea between
May and June, EAL had to stop its commercial flight to northern
border cities.
</P>
<P>
The EAL official said that its running cost has also increased
remarkably due to diversion of routes for security reasons. Last
year, the EAL had to transfer its hub to Nairobi, Kenya, for a
period of time which witnessed a fierce battle between Ethiopia
and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
According to Bisrat, his company will maintain its routes, but
refrain from introducing new ones.
</P>
<P>
The EAL, established 53 years ago, currently flies to about 50
international destinations, out of which 25 are in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
