<HEADLINE> 165 Oil Workers Set Free by Hostage Takers in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Gunmen in south eastern Nigeria
left two oil rigs on Friday afternoon where they had held 165
workers hostage, according to reports by the multinational oil
company Royal Dutch Shell here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
All the workers, who had been held hostage for the past five
days on the rigs in the Niger Delta, are safe, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The local ethnic Ijaw gunmen stormed the rigs on Monday,
demanding jobs and cash, seizing hostages included 145 Nigerians,
seven citizens from the United States, five Britons and a number
of Australians and Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
The company reached an agreement with representatives of the
hostage takers on Wednesday to free the captives after their hard
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Militant youth in the Niger Delta where most of Nigeria's oil
wealth is produced frequently take foreign workers hostage in
order to draw attention to their cause for more government
allocation, demanding money or jobs. 
</P>
