<HEADLINE> 1 Million Orphans Caused by AIDS in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS scourge has ravaged
Kenya leaving behind over 1 million orphans, according to the
country's National AIDS Control Council.
</P>
<P>
Meshack Ndolo, national coordinator of the council in charge of
advocacy and information, said in Kuria District in western Kenya
that the epidemic was claiming 500 people daily in the country,
the Kenya Times newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ndolo appealed local residents for openness in discussing the
AIDS scourge and advised the public to jealously guard against
immoral behavior that could lead to contracting the disease,
saying that youth at the age of 15-24 were the hardest hit by the
killer disease.
</P>
<P>
He said the government plans to start AIDS education to be
included in the school curriculum, adding teachers will be trained
on the subject through in-service.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator also urged each classroom in school to have a
special AIDS education campaign corner which will update
information on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that since Kenya found the first AIDS case in
1984, an estimated 1.1 million Kenyans have so far perished due to
the HIV/AIDS scourge and the cost of the pandemic to the country's
economy is estimated at 10 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
