<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets up Power Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
established an Emergency Electricity Coordinating Committee on the
implementation of the emergency power supply project.
</P>
<P>
The committee, chaired by Finance Minister Chris Okemo, will
oversee an emergency thermal power project of 105 megawatts, the
state-run Kenya Times newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also review and approve the decision of the
emergency power technical team and coordinate with relevant arms
of the government in the implementation of emergency power supply.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has experienced a prolonged drought which has led to the
lower levels of the dams, affecting the hydropower generation. The
country introduced power rationing last September and intensified
the rationing in early June.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has also taken a series of measures to
combat the drought and power shortage, including importing more
power from Uganda and installing emergency diesel generators.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the power rationing crisis has made the
country's economy losing 8 billion shillings (about 107 million U.
S. dollars) monthly. 
