<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army's Withdrawal From Congo Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The withdrawal of Uganda People's
Defence Forces (UPDF) from the Democratic Republic of the Congo (
DRC) has been hampered by bad weather and technical problems, Army
Spokesman Phinehas Katirima told Xinhua Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two planes, which left the Entebbe International Airport on
Thursday to pick the second batch of soldiers, returned empty
after failing to land at the Buta airport in the northern DRC due
to the poor weather.
</P>
<P>
"The planes could not land because of the weather, they had to
come back," said Katirima.
</P>
<P>
The planes which were supposed to fly back to Buta on Friday
failed to make it again after one of them reportedly knocked a
building.
</P>
<P>
Katirima said however that the planes did not go back because
of some technical problem.
</P>
<P>
The second batch of forces or some 300 soldiers were expected
to return in Friday's aborted trip. The first batch of 450 solders
arrived at the Entebbe Airport on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The five battalions, a total of some 4,000 soldiers, were given
order in June to pull out of the DRC. They have been assembled in
Buta waiting to be flown home.
</P>
<P>
According to Katirima, the withdrawal continues until the last
soldier is flown out of Buta to the Entebbe Airport.
</P>
<P>
The return of soldiers follows the demilitarization of the
northeastern city of Kisangani, the third largest city of the DRC,
where they had been deployed. The Ugandan troops and their Rwandan
counterparts fought each other in Kisangani in May and June this
year, causing heavy civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda send their troops to the DRC to back rival
rebel factions fighting against President of the DRC Laurent
Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
