<HEADLINE> Annan Concerned at Detention of Four Foreigners by Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday voiced his concern over the detention of two
Britons and two Canadians, who were accused by Yugoslavia of
terrorism and spying, and called for their earliest release.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in a statement issued by his spokesman here that he
"is much concerned over the detention" by the Yugoslav Army since
Tuesday of the two British members of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The two Britons are seconded to the United Nations Interim
Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK), the statement said. "He
also expresses his concern over the detention of the two Canadian
citizens who were arrested at the same time."
</P>
<P>
"The seconded OSCE officials are members of the UNMIK mission,
" and they "are entitled to the privileges and immunities of
United Nations staff members," the statement said. "He demands
immediate access to the staff members by representatives of the
Organization."
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General also calls upon the Yugoslav
authorities to honor their obligations under the Vienna Convention
on Consular Relations and grant immediate access to those detained
by representatives of the United Kingdom and Canada," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He calls for the earliest release by the Yugoslav authorities
of the detained personnel," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav army arrested the Britons with two Canadians on
Tuesday night in the area between Montenegro, a Yugoslav republic,
and Kosovo, a Serb province in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia broke off diplomatic relations with Britain in 1999
when the NATO launched 78-day unilateral air strike on the Balkan
country. Both Britain and Canada are NATO members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
