<HEADLINE> Brazil Restructures Debt with 40-Year Securities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Central Bank started
Friday in New York a swapping operation to exchange foreign debt
bonds for 40-year securities, with an option to buy them back
after 2015.
</P>
<P>
A Central Bank communique says that the exchange of the foreign
debt obligations will be made through a public auction in the
Internet, coordinated by the Chase Securities Goldman Sachs and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter banks.
</P>
<P>
The auction will end August 9, at 15:00 New York time, and the
result will be announced the following day.
</P>
<P>
This swapping operation of old bonds for new ones represents,
according to the Central Bank, one step forward in the country's
Program of Administration of External Liability, aimed at
improving the Brazilian foreign debt profile.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has about 232 billion U.S.dollars of foreign debt, the
biggest one in Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
