<HEADLINE> Colombian President Calls Clinton's Visit Very Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres
Pastrana Friday called "very important" U.S. President Bill
Clinton's visit to the country scheduled for August 30.
</P>
<P>
"We are very aware that he (Clinton) will be here very soon,"
Pastrana told the press after a military ceremony in Bogota to
mark the Army Day.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Gustavo Bell described Clinton's upcoming visit
as "a show of confidence in the effort we are doing to push this
country forward."
</P>
<P>
Bogota printed media said that the U.S. president will arrive
at the Caribbean resort city of Cartagena in the north of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said the visit will be the first of a U.S. president
in many years.
</P>
<P>
George Bush was the last U.S. president to visit Colombia, who
did it in 1990 in Cartagena to attend an anti-drug summit.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton will make his first visit to Colombia on
August 30 to discuss how to help the country crack down on drug
production, the White House said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Clinton will express his support for Colombia
to fight drug trafficking and strengthen the economy, the White
House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will be accompanied by a bipartisan group of U.S.
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed a directive on Friday to express his support for
President Pastrana's effort to fight drug trafficking and seek
peace with rebel forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
