<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council to Convene Summit on World Peace and Security (Updated with background information) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday announced that the 15-nation body will convene the summit
on September 7 on the Council's role in the maintenance of
international peace and security, particularly in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was contained in a statement read to the
press by the president of the Security Council, Agam Hasmy of
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
 the statement said that "the members of the Security Council
are looking forward to the Millennium Summit of the United Nations,
which will provide a unique opportunity to strengthen the role of
the United Nations in meeting the challenges of the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
"Conscious of the important tasks facing the international
community in the area of peacekeeping, the members of the Security
Council have decided that the Council will meet on September 7,
2000 at the level of Heads of State and Government to consider the
topic 'Ensuring an effective role of the Security Council in the
maintenance of international peace and security, particularly in
Africa," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will hold the summit on the sideline of
the U.N. Millennium Summit, scheduled for September 6-8 in the U.N.
headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Security Council believe that such a
meeting will make a valuable contribution towards achieving the
major purpose of the Millennium Summit aimed at strengthening the
United Nations," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council summit is to be chaired by President Alpha
Oumar Konare of Mali, who holds the presidency of the Security
Council for the month of September.
</P>
<P>
This is the second summit by the 15-nation body since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council, which groups five
permanent members and 10 non-permanent members, has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of the peace and security in
the world at large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
