<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges Taliban to Reverse Edict on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday urged the Afghan warring party the Taliban to
reverse its edict barring Afghan women from working with U.N.
agencies and international non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, the largest warring party in Afghanistan, issued
an edict early last month which barred Afghan women from working
with national and foreign agencies and non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Annan, who is now in Africa for a visit,
expressed deep concern over the humanitarian impact of the edict.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief noted that these restrictions on women's
employment came at a time when Afghanistan was facing a severe
drought and an unprecedented food deficit, and were expected to
impact negatively on the aid community's ability to provide
urgently-required humanitarian assistance to the most vulnerable,
particularly women and children.
</P>
<P>
Annan underscored the critical need to provide humanitarian
assistance to the Afghan population and urged the Taliban to
reconsider their position in order to avert further unnecessary
human suffering.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations began the negotiations with the Taliban on
the issue three weeks ago, hoping that the issue would be resolved
soon so as to avoid any negative impact on the provision of
humanitarian aid at such a critical moment for the Afghan people.
The country is currently suffering from one of the worst droughts
in addition to the effects of the 22 years of civil strife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
