<HEADLINE> Mexico Sets Deadline for U.S. To Fulfill Sugar Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is in compliance with the elimination of customs tariffs
agreed on in the North America Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), said
president of the Chamber of the National Sugar and Alcohol
Industry Carlos Seoane on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The sugar sector will not accept to export less than the
surplus of the sweet substance, equivalent to almost 575,000 tons,
because so far at this time, 200 million U.S. dollars worth of
sugar exports have been lost, said Seoane.
</P>
<P>
Seoane said after meeting with Commerce and Industry Minister
Herminio Blanco that the chamber will demand to stop the imports
of U.S. fructose, according to a safeguard foreseen in NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
The sugar producers position is radical because they will only
accept to export to the United States the total of their surplus,
as agreed in NAFTA, said the chamber official.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Department of Commerce representatives said the way to
solve the problem is to continue the dialogue, and that the
contacts within the parts will continue next week.
</P>
<P>
This situation has seriously damaged the Mexican sugar industry,
which produces sugarcane on 650,000 hectares and has 60 sugar
mills in 15 states of the country which give direct employment to
360,000 people and two million indirect jobs, said Seoane.
</P>
<P>
"We only demand what is just, to export all the sugar surplus,
as agreed. We insist that it must be the whole surplus of 550,000
tons," Seoane added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
