<HEADLINE> U.N. Asks Its Female Employees in Afghanistan to Stay Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Friday asked its female employees in Afghanistan to stay home out
of concern of their safety.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Taliban, the largest warring party in
the country, refuses to reverse its edict barring Afghan women
working with U.N. agencies and international non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said the United Nations had no choice
but to caution all Afghan women directly employed by the
organization and its programme to stay at home until further
notice, for their protection.
</P>
<P>
Annan pressed the Taliban to lift the edict.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban issued an edict early last month which barred
Afghan women from working with U.N. agencies and international non-
governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations began negotiations with the Taliban three
weeks ago in an attempt to solve the issue. But no result has
yielded.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations, women play a key role in
providing relief in impoverished, war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's restrictions will cause negative impact on the
provision of international humanitarian aid to the country. In
Kabul alone, an estimated one-quarter of the population of 1.8
million are dependent on aid for survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
