<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President To Visit OPEC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
will visit the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
member countries from Aug. 7 to 15, announced Mines and Energy
Minister Ali Rodriguezon on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chavez will examine in those nations, in defense of the oil
prices, compliance with the agreements on the extraction of oil
adopted by the OPEC, said Rodriguez, who is OPEC president and
will accompany Chavez during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Chavez will personally invite each one of the OPEC heads of
state to attend the second summit of the organization scheduled
for the last days of September in Caracas.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said the OPEC has an excess production of 200,000 to
700,000 barrels per day, and the quotations that have dropped last
month from historical records will collapse by the end of the year
if the market is bloated.
</P>
<P>
The 11 OPEC nations agreed in March and June to increase their
output to stop the rise in the oil price, which went to its higher
levels of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC basket of crudes for export was quoted August 4 at 26.
12 dollars per barrel, 14 percent under the top 29.97 dollars of
the middle of June.
</P>
<P>
The experts attributed the drop in the price to reports that
Saudi Arabia, the most important producer of the OPEC,
unilaterally increased its production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
